<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 25 日星期二 12:12:53 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Evangelicals Can Have Revival or Nostalgia—But Not Both]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国福音派面临的危机并不一定是坏消息。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/bSfBj4QpW4w5PU7vbslLiHWzkys=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/moore_evangelicalcrisis/original.jpg" alt="教堂破裂的插图。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>凯蒂·马丁的照片插图。资料来源：罗伯托·施密特/法新社/盖蒂。</figcaption></figure><i>想了解更多拉塞尔摩尔的消息吗？ 9 月 28 日至 29 日，您可以在大西洋音乐节上看到他和 Tim Alberta 以及其他大胆的声音。</i><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/live/atlantic-festival-2023/"><i>在这里</i></a>获取您的通行证<i>。</i><br><br>年轻的福音派人士问我的第一个问题是如何与他们的父母和导师相处，他们想要谈论文化战争政治和互联网阴谋论而不是祈祷或圣经。这些年轻人致力于基督教信仰，但他们对教会的未来感到绝望和愤世嫉俗。由于这个标签与政治类别相混淆，几乎没有人再称自己为“福音派”。 “有时我觉得自己疯了，”几天前一位牧师对我说。 “没有人看到教会正处于危机之中吗？”<br><br>它的确是。我是一名保守的福音派人士，曾担任美南浸信会公共政策部门的负责人。多年来，我因反对唐纳德·特朗普以及对种族正义和教会性虐待等问题的看法而受到福音派的强烈反对，其中包括来自我最亲密的盟友和朋友的反对。我几乎不认为自己是一个“持不同政见者”。相反，我相信我还是我一直以来的样子：一个忠诚的美南浸信会福音派信徒，试图运用我从儿童主日学校学到的关于基本基督教道德和正义的知识。尽管如此，我仍感觉自己是一个被遗弃者和异端分子。我感到无家可归。两年前，我离开了我所热爱的美南浸信会世界。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/06/evangelical-church-pastors-political-radicalization/629631/">蒂姆·艾伯塔：政治如何毒害福音派教会</a><br><br>我知道其他福音派人士也有类似的感受。我很难想象有哪个会众不会因政治时刻的动荡而分裂——或者因分裂迫在眉睫而处于紧张的紧张状态。这应该是我们教会复兴的时刻。复兴是美国福音派中一个有着悠久历史的概念，它植根于圣经，它说一个已经变得冷漠、死气沉沉的民族可以在信仰上得到更新。这是一种从死里复活。<br><br>然而，复兴的语言现在充满了愤世嫉俗，并与美国福音派的一些最糟糕的方面联系在一起。富有创业精神的美国福音派为“复兴”建立了一个纲领性的结构——无论是在像我长大的那样的圣经带小教堂的春季和秋季聚会安排中，还是在全国各地举办的大型体育场活动中，比如摇滚音乐会。正如<i>《卫报》</i>在 2016 年总统选举后的一篇社论中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/jan/15/the-guardian-view-on-american-christianity-change-and-decay">指出的</a>那样，“最终，市场驱动的宗教催生了市场驱动的真理观，这种发展最终摧毁了美国保守的基督教，让它落入伪君子和小贩的手中。”<br><br>一些福音派基督徒将“复兴”与回到神话般的黄金时代混为一谈。一代人之前，一位福音派领袖表示，宗教右翼的目标应该是 20 世纪 50 年代的美国，只是没有性别歧视和种族主义。如今，就连这些资格也正在消失。调查显示，与其他宗教团体和普通民众相比，白人福音派最容易受到“大替代”理论等白人民族主义比喻的影响，他们的机构将对种族正义的最基本承诺讽刺为“批判种族理论”。那些在承认性虐待掩盖事实方面进展缓慢的教派，很快就会驱逐那些他们认为过于肯定女性领导地位的教会。<br><br>然而，怀旧与复兴的混淆不仅仅是 MAGA 右翼福音派的领域。<i>许多主流福音派人士认为，我们只是在等待一段混乱的时刻结束：如果我们能够安然度过 2016 年总统选举、疫情、种族歧视抗议和强烈反对、2020 年总统选举以及看似持续不断的福音派领袖性虐待丑闻，那么我们最终将安全地回到 2015 年。这显然不会发生。</i><br><br>危机动摇了旧的秩序——正如使徒保罗所说，撕裂了由“木头、干草、残茬”组成的东西（哥林多前书 3:12）。现在，每一刻都可能是一场大灾难——我们周围一直存在的一切都被揭露——因此每一刻都是一个做出决定的时刻。<br><br>将复兴视为回归某个真实或想象的伟大时刻的想法不仅是虚幻的，而且是危险的。在二战后被认为是田园诗般的基督教美国，福音派传教士 AW Tozer 写道：“我深思熟虑的观点是，在目前的情况下，我们根本不想要复兴。我们今天所知道的那种基督教在美国的广泛复兴可能会被证明是一场道德悲剧，我们一百年后也无法从中恢复过来。”托泽尔知道，复兴与怀旧的混淆可能正是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2022/august-web-only/body-christ-keeps-score-spiritual-trauma-sbc-church-abuse.html">当代心理学家告诉我们的关于创伤的</a>内容：<i>没有修复的东西会重复。</i><br><br>这就是为什么美国福音派面临的危机并不一定是坏消息。许多人，包括我自己，都对我们所看到的福音派运动的分裂感到遗憾。曾经一起领导事工的人们不再互相交谈。几十年来一起祈祷的人们现在互相说：“我什至不知道你是谁了！”所有这一切都是在美国文化的背景下进行的，而美国文化似乎也在分裂——这一过程因中介机构的崩溃和社交媒体生态系统的发展而加速——社会心理学家乔纳森·海特<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/05/social-media-democracy-trust-babel/629369/">在本杂志中将其与圣经巴别塔的毁灭进行了比较</a>。<br><br>然而，巴别塔的问题并不在于碎片化。问题在于团结。建造者们因自己的傲慢而联合起来，建造了最终会毁灭他们的东西。语言的混乱和人口的分散都是上帝的杰作。答案不是重新组合旧的建筑计划并重新开始。答案就在下一章——乌尔的亚伯兰，一个孤独的人物，他听到了一个应许，长途跋涉进入沙漠，却不知道要去哪里。<br><br>解决美国福音派面临的可信度危机的答案并不是为“福音派灵魂”而战，让一个团体获胜并驱逐失败者。约翰·卫斯理和查尔斯·卫斯理并没有取代 18 世纪的英国国教会创建卫理公会，但他们的革新运动仍然在全世界和其他新教教派中引起共鸣。比利·格雷厄姆曾在许多原教旨主义领域被逐出，而他正是在这些领域学会了传播福音，但他却在他的导师们无法做到的地方传播了福音。<br><br>相反，答案始终如一：那些希望坚持旧时代宗教的人必须认识到上帝正在做一些新的事情。旧的联盟和联盟正在瓦解。许多基督徒感到的迷失方向、幻灭感以及政治和宗教“无家可归”的感觉不是一个需要克服的问题，而是这个过程的关键部分。福音派基督教最好的见解是，任何朝圣都不能从确定的路线图开始，而必须从信仰的呼喊开始，就像被错误地标记为怀疑者的高贵门徒托马斯一样，“主啊，我们不知道你要去哪里。我们怎么能认识路呢？” （约翰福音 14:5）。<br><br>怀旧——尤其是煽动者和独裁者所利用的怀旧——无法保护宗教信仰，因为它利用宗教作为实现世俗目的的工具，留下了精神空虚。基督教会仍然需要人们的有机运动，提醒我们其他人，个人转变还有希望，危机带来恩典。<br><br> CS刘易斯指出，上帝几乎从未应允的一个祈祷是“再来一次”。刘易斯写道，只要我们看到它们的本来面目——回忆，而不是蓝图，我们对“过去的黄金时刻”的怀念就可以滋养和维持。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cslewisinstitute.org/resources/reflections-september-2016/">刘易斯说：</a> “如果我们正确地埋藏在过去，而我们不会痛苦地试图唤起过去，它们就会长出精致的花朵。” “别管球茎，新花就会开出来。把它们捡起来，希望通过抚摸和嗅闻来获得去年的花朵，但你什么也得不到。”<br><br>如果福音派否认我们面前危机的严重性，而只是选择那种能够保留昔日联盟和权力结构的公共关系，我们将失去一代人，他们渴望看看福音是真实的，还是只是动员选民或向客户推销的另一种手段。我们将发现自己又陷入了一场竞赛，看看我们可以利用什么样的力量来实现这一目标——一如既往，这将使我们站在钉十字架的一边，而不是站在被钉十字架的一边。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/10/evangelical-trump-christians-politics/620469/">彼得·韦纳：福音派教会正在分裂</a><br><br>教会必须停止那些试图保住过去圣经带的疯狂言论和极度缺乏信心。相反，那些配得上<i>“福音派”</i>这个词的人应该培养喜乐、平静、充实的信仰，祈求根植于非常古老的事物的新事物——即对个人信仰和圣经权威的承诺。<br><br>这不是从宣言和战略路线图开始，而是从小规模的决定开始，以重新唤醒福音派所宣称的上帝的敬畏。我们必须重新把注意力集中在皈依上，而不是文化战争上，并真正阅读圣经，而不是挖掘其中的段落来赢得争论。没有人可以单独改变“福音派运动”。改变首先是一个人一个人地发生，然后是一个又一个会众的改变。如果我们中有足够多的人愿意将这种无家可归的感觉视为我们的新常态——我们本来就应该处于这种状态——那么我们就可以重新燃起对一个不同的王国称之为家的渴望。<br><br>在一个为让美国再次伟大而疲惫不堪的国家，也许我们需要的是让福音派重生。<br><br>最终，这不是一个策略。这是一个祈祷。<br><br><small><i>本文改编自拉塞尔·摩尔即将出版的新书《</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/losing-our-religion-an-altar-call-for-evangelical-america-russell-moore/9780593541784?affiliate_id=atl-347">失去我们的宗教：美国福音派的祭坛呼吁》</a> <i>。</i></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/christian-evangelical-church-division-politics/674810/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/christian-evangelical-church-division-politics/674810/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[What to Read When You Want to Learn a New Skill]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这些书可能会诱使你开始新的追求，并扩大你对自己能力的认识。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/rKaC0goYzwabGHwRybphGxsgMns=/0x0:8000x4500/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/MakeBook_A_noNumbers/original.jpg" alt="制作一本小书的步骤图" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>本·丹泽 (Ben Denzer) 为《大西洋月刊》</figcaption></figure>在过去的六个月里，我一直沉迷于家务管理——我所有以前的室友都可以证明，我以前对此既没有兴趣也没有能力。我制定了清洁时间表，花了太多时间思考不同织物的相对优点，并且在将洗碗机放入洗碗机时变得更加清爽。我什至最近发现自己将其描述为“有趣”。<br><br>我将这一切归咎于一本书：谢丽尔·门德尔森（Cheryl Mendelson）的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/home-comforts-the-art-and-science-of-keeping-house-cheryl-mendelson/9780743272865?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>《家庭舒适》（Home Comforts）</em></a> 。这本不太可能的畅销书首次出版于 1999 年，包含近 900 页的实用建议——洗碗的正确方法、家具蜡的使用。吸引我的是它精彩的开篇文章，门德尔森是一位小说家、教授和律师，他在文中论证了守家的重要性和尊严——这种行为“让你的家充满活力，将它变成一个独立的小社会，一个有自己的方式和节奏的重要场所。”虽然我仍然是一个随意的管家，但我越来越相信家政既是一门艺术，也是一门科学，一项其意义远远超出保持家清洁的事业。<br><br>下面的七本书还描述了专注于某项技能或手艺的经历，并深入探讨了日常活动（例如运动或学习外语）可以告诉我们今天的生活方式。这些书建议，仔细观察人类的任何努力，你会发现我们与自然世界、历史、其他文化以及我们自己的身体的关系的教训。他们如此生动地捕捉了他们所描述的追求的满足感，以至于你可能会受到诱惑去从事园艺、长跑或书籍装订，并扩大你对自己能力的认识。<br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/in-other-words-jhumpa-lahiri/9781101911464?affiliate_id=atl-347"><strong><em>换句话说</em></strong></a><strong>，作者：Jhumpa Lahiri</strong><br><br> 2012年，拉希里搬到了罗马，并停止了英语阅读和写作，转而沉浸在意大利语中。这一系列双语反思——左边是意大利语原文，右边是安·戈德斯坦的英文翻译——描绘了她对罗曼语的热爱，从她在佛罗伦萨之旅中第一次听到罗曼语时的“轻率、荒谬的渴望”，到随后 20 年的语言课程、辅导和勤奋的自学。她承认，走向流利的过程是“一次持续的尝试”。她混淆了类似的单词，例如<em>schiacciare</em> （“粉碎”）和<em>scacciare</em> （“驱逐”），使用了错误的介词，并且无法完全掌握何时使用简单或不完美的过去时。当她开始用意大利语创作故事时，她意识到她永远无法达到用英语创作的能力。但意大利语重新给她的阅读带来了神秘、愉悦和强烈的感觉：“每一页似乎都笼罩着一层薄薄的薄雾，”她写道。 “这些障碍激励着我。每一座新建筑似乎都是一个奇迹。每一个未知的单词都是宝石。”在她的好奇心之下，隐藏着一个更深层次的论点——出于对新技能的热爱，从根本上来说，投入新技能是充满希望的，甚至是超越的。 “我越感觉不完美，”她写道，“我就越感觉自己还活着。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/the-terrible-downside-of-ai-language-translation/674687/">阅读：在为时已晚之前学习一门外语</a><br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/beyond-a-boundary-c-l-r-james/9780822355632?affiliate_id=atl-347"><strong><em>超越边界</em></strong></a><strong>，作者：CLR James</strong><br><br>特立尼达学者詹姆斯最出名的可能是他的马克思主义著作和对加勒比独立的倡导。鲜为人知的是他对板球的痴迷。詹姆斯一生都沉浸在这项运动中：他专注于比赛而不是学业，这让他的家人感到失望，他为特立尼达的一流俱乐部效力，并最终在英格兰作为记者报道板球。他甚至将自己的激进主义归功于这项运动。他写道，“早在我意识到之前，板球就让我陷入了政治”——部分原因是岛上阶级和种族的紧张局势在社会分层的俱乐部中上演。 <em>《超越界限》</em>证明，如果不考虑板球运动的历史、社会和文化背景，就不可能理解它。在这本书最雄心勃勃的时刻，它论证了板球在现代英国历史中的基础地位及其作为戏剧和视觉艺术的地位。即使你对这项运动一无所知，詹姆斯也能传达出它的丰富性——击球手的风格如何反映个人个性和社会的优先事项，以及这项运动如何毫不费力地将其追随者与更广阔的世界联系起来。<br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/onward-and-upward-in-the-garden-katherine-s-white/9781590178508?affiliate_id=atl-347"><strong><em>在花园里前进和向上</em></strong></a><strong>，作者：凯瑟琳·S·怀特</strong><br><br>怀特将她的园艺习惯描述为“粗心”、“懒惰”和“业余”，但她为<em>《纽约客》</em>收集的园艺专栏中所体现的挑剔的眼光和严格的品味令人愉悦。怀特是该杂志的第一位小说编辑——她是许多著名作家的早期出版商，其中包括她未来的丈夫 EB 怀特——在这些专栏中，她对 1958 年至 1970 年间的园艺书籍和种子目录进行了清晰的评估，不仅考虑了它们的散文，还考虑了易用性、排版、纸张质量和色彩再现。到处都是鲜花盛开的生活的一瞥。冬天，她穿过一座种满植物的房子，担心仙客来的位置和非洲紫罗兰的温度。她告诉我们，有一次，她试图在冰冻的缅因州花园里种植百合花，结果出现了“我和我热切的家人用撬棍攻击花坛的滑稽场面”。她对胡须鸢尾、葫芦、大丽花和剑兰的看法都充满了幽默和魅力，让我忍不住梦想着我自己的花园会是什么样子。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/education/archive/2020/09/teaching-healing-power-garden-class/616198/">阅读：花园课的治愈力量</a><br><br><strong>詹姆斯·雷班克斯的</strong><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-shepherd-s-life-modern-dispatches-from-an-ancient-landscape-james-rebanks/9781250060266?affiliate_id=atl-347"><strong><em>《牧羊人的生活》</em></strong></a><br><br>将目光投向英格兰湖区青翠的群山，你可能会想起华兹华斯和浪漫主义诗人为未受人类影响的荒野写下的赞歌。雷班克斯是一位牧羊人，他的家人在那片土地上生活了几个世纪，他反驳了这些关于他的家乡的诗意形象。他在发人深省的回忆录中写道：“这里的每一英亩，都是由过去一万年来男人和女人的行为所定义的。”作者将羊的照顾和饲养变得非常有趣，想象了每年夏天牧羊人从山顶上收集羊群的协调一致的钳形动作，以及春天产下小羊的费力工作，有时需要徒手伸手。到最后，选择哪只公羊与母羊交配开始似乎是一个高风险的艺术决定。雷班克斯将他对传统农业的描绘视为现代生活的对立面（他发现在牛津的一段时间基本上“毫无意义且空虚”）。他令人信服的批评邀请读者寻找更根深蒂固、历史悠久的生活方式。<br><br><strong>村上春树《</strong> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/what-i-talk-about-when-i-talk-about-running-a-memoir-haruki-murakami/9780307389831?affiliate_id=atl-347"><strong><em>当我谈论跑步时我在谈论什么》</em></strong></a><br><br>这本经典的业余回忆录讲述了村上隆为 2005 年纽约市马拉松比赛进行训练的过程，并反思了认真跑步的生活。这本书接近于自助——章节标题包括“苦难是可选的”和“我通过每天跑步学到的关于写小说的大部分知识”——但整个过程中乐观的辞职气氛改变了它的基调。 “生活基本上是不公平的，”村上写道。 “但即使在不公平的情况下，我认为也有可能寻求一种公平。”你根本无法控制比赛当天发生的事情，就像村上无法控制自己衰老的身体和较慢的完赛时间一样，更不用说他“像一个旧手提箱一样”随身携带的顽固、回避的性格了。这本书令人耳目一新，没有劝告每个人都去跑步。 （事实上​​，作者认为强迫人们这样做是“毫无意义的折磨”，没错。）但他在考艾岛或马萨诸塞州剑桥慢跑的场景，脑子里只想着清晨清新的空气和“我的脚步声、呼吸声和心跳声，所有这些都以独特的多重节奏混合在一起”，这是他们自己的说服力。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/06/the-2189-mile-marathon/559112/">阅读：</a><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/06/the-2189-mile-marathon/559112/">跑 2,189 英里马拉松的智慧</a><br><br><strong><em>精通程度</em></strong><strong>，作者：安妮·特雷梅尔·威尔考克斯</strong><br><br><em>《精通程度》</em>的第一部分将读者直接带入书籍保护的深处，并且非常引人入胜。威尔考克斯从 1817 年印刷的一本日益恶化的书上切下书脊，拆开装订，然后在去离子水中清洗书页。她小心翼翼地用日本小麦淀粉糊修补裂口，这种糊是用一种叫做“烹饪搅拌”的设备制备的。我知道了一些我不知道有名字的书的名称：例如，连接在精装书书脊上的条纹绳是一个端带。 1987 年，威尔科克斯成为著名图书管理员威廉·安东尼 (William Anthony) 的第一位女学徒，之后他因肝癌去世。她的回忆录详细描述了爱荷华大学图书馆保护部门工作台上的生活，在那里，她在安东尼耐心的注视下修改 15 世纪的古版古书和<em>《草叶集》</em>版本，开始装订书籍。这也是对学徒期本质、对手艺从业者之间的相互学习以及对那些通过拥护自己的知识和理想的学生继续生活的老师的感人思考。<br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-curse-of-the-boyfriend-sweater-essays-on-crafting-alanna-okun/9781250095633?affiliate_id=atl-347"><strong><em>男友毛衣的诅咒</em></strong></a><strong>，作者：阿兰娜·奥肯</strong><br><br>奥肯断言，大多数人之所以沉迷于自己的爱好，是因为他们在寻求一种特定的满足感：“这种微小但持续的运动可以帮助他们新陈代谢宇宙，并构成他们身份的一部分。”有些人演奏乐器；有些人则演奏乐器。一些鱼。奥肯最喜欢的活动是编织，这是她一生的追求，还有钩针和刺绣，所有这些都<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/04/crafts-coronavirus-quarantine-stress-relief/609187/">为她创造了远离喧嚣世界的避风港</a>。在这些极其脆弱的文章中，编织婴儿羊毛衫和钩编巨大的毯子不仅是令人愉快的消遣，而且是情感的生命线，而奥肯则在应对两个朋友和祖父母去世的悲伤，以及浪漫的痛苦和与焦虑的斗争。 “一个工艺项目，”奥肯写道，“让你可以在手中握住一些具体的东西，即使你周围的一切都在旋转且难以辨认。”她明确表示，手工制作也非常有趣。奥肯带着她在地铁和海滩上编织，并诙谐地列出了她从纤维艺术努力中获得的技能。通过她的眼睛，我们看到了“一大堆双色绿色羊毛、三团未漂白的棉球、一小束丝绸”的无限潜力。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/lifelong-learning-new-skill-book-recommendations/674807/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/lifelong-learning-new-skill-book-recommendations/674807/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[AI Companies Are Trying to Have It Both Ways]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在同意护栏的同时，行业领导者承认了他们的产品可能存在的风险，但同时又没有停止激烈的竞争。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/0ZDsF3pb7JLrD1vZF7N7_p36pPs=/0x172:5851x3463/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1561046611-1/original.jpg" alt="七位人工智能公司领导人与拜登总统在白宫罗斯福厅" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>安娜摇钱树/盖蒂</figcaption></figure><small><i>这是</i>《大西洋<i>日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>在这里注册。</i></a></small><br><br>上周，七家科技公司出现在白宫，同意自愿对人工智能的使用采取保护措施。在承诺采取这些措施时，这些公司承认其产品的潜在风险，但同时又不停止激烈的竞争。<br><br>首先，这是<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>的四个新故事：<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/raj-chetty-paper-harvard-ivy-league-elite/674803/">为什么你要关心这12所大学</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/clear-airport-security-lines-tsa-infrastructure/674809/">完美的服务让机场所有人都讨厌你</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/wealthy-liberal-suburbs-economic-segregation-scarsdale/674792/">自由郊区有自己的边界墙。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/tick-bite-saliva-infection-spread/674804/">蜱虫正在获胜。</a></li><strong>方便的手势</strong><br><br>当我第一次听到有人将 2010 年代的硅谷与文艺复兴时期的佛罗伦萨进行比较时，我正坐在宿舍大厅的斜线研讨会室里。 2013 年，我当时是湾区的一名大学生，教授和同龄人经常谈论我们如何处于一个独特的繁荣时期，这将重塑人类。在某些方面，事实证明这是正确的——在科技时代，当 Twitter 和 Facebook 等公司刚刚上市、初创企业大量涌现时，确实改变了一切（尽管当时的技术乐观主义压力在接下来的几年里有所凝固）。<br><br>今天早上，我在阅读 Ross Andersen 在<i>《大西洋月刊</i>》九月号上发表的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/sam-altman-openai-chatgpt-gpt-4/674764/">新文章</a>时再次思考了这种观点，该文章介绍了 OpenAI 及其首席执行官 Sam Altman。 “你们即将进入最伟大的黄金时代，”罗斯听到奥特曼对一群学生说。另一方面，奥特曼表示，人工智能革命将“不同于以前的技术变革”，它将“就像一种新型社会”。奥特曼相信人工智能将重塑世界，这是显而易见的。这种转变究竟会如何进行尚不清楚。近几个月来，随着人工智能工具得到广泛使用和兴趣，OpenAI 及其竞争对手一直在进行有趣的舞蹈：他们在提升技术的同时，也多次以世界末日的方式警告其潜在危害。<br><br>周五，来自七家主要人工智能公司（OpenAI、亚马逊、Anthropic、谷歌、Inflection、Meta 和微软）的领导人会见了乔·拜登，并<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/21/us/politics/ai-regulation-biden.html">同意采取一系列自愿保障措施</a>。这些公司承诺， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/22/technology/ai-regulation-white-house.html">有时措辞含糊</a>，将采取行动，例如发布有关安全测试的信息、与学术界和政府分享研究成果、报告其系统中的“漏洞”，以及开发告诉人们内容何时由人工智能生成的机制。其中许多措施都是公司已经采取的措施。而且由于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2023/07/21/fact-sheet-biden-harris-administration-secures-voluntary-commitments-from-leading-artificial-intelligence-companies-to-manage-the-risks-posed-by-ai/">白宫做出的</a>承诺是自愿的，因此它们不是可执行的法规。尽管如此，它们还是允许这些公司和拜登向公众发出信号，表明他们正在致力于人工智能安全。在同意这些自愿预防措施的同时，这些公司承认其产品可能存在的风险，同时在激烈的竞争中几乎没有做出任何牺牲。<br><br> “对于人工智能公司来说，这是一个梦想的场景，他们可以通过假装解决了问题来缓解监管压力，同时最终继续照常营业，”监视技术监督项目执行董事阿尔伯特·福克斯·卡恩(Albert Fox Cahn)在一封电子邮件中告诉我。他补充说，其他产品存在安全风险的公司，例如汽车制造商和核电站，无法进行自我监管。<br><br>奥特曼已成为人工智能行业的主角，他声称自己既是该技术的冠军，又是房间里一个理性的成年人。据罗斯报道，OpenAI 首席执行官今年春天进行了一次国际聆听之旅，会见了国家元首和立法者。今年 5 月，他在国会面前表示，他希望人工智能受到监管——这既可以被视为一种对公民负责的举措，也可以被视为将部分责任转移给国会的一种方式，而国会可能会采取缓慢的行动。到目前为止，这些对话和国会听证会还没有形成全面的、具有约束力的法规。公司不断成长。<br><br>人工智能行业的领导者对他们的工具的风险直言不讳。几个月前，包括奥特曼和比尔·盖茨在内的人工智能杰出人物签署了一份一句话声明，其中写道：“与流行病和核战争等其他社会规模风险一样，减轻人工智能带来的灭绝风险应该成为全球优先事项。” （ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/03/31/technology/sam-altman-open-ai-chatgpt.html">奥特曼</a>和其他人工智能开发者<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/richard-rhodes-making-of-the-atomic-bomb-ai/674777/">邀请人们将其与罗伯特·奥本海默进行比较</a>。）但世界末日的警告也使这项技术听起来相当具有开创性。上个月，我的同事 Matteo Wong <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/06/ai-regulation-sam-altman-bill-gates/674278/">写道</a>，这一信息不仅令人震惊，而且还自私自利：“首席执行官们就像半神一样，正在运用一种具有变革性的技术，如火、电、核裂变或引发大流行的病毒。不投资的话你就是个傻子。”<br><br>另一个好处是：正如我的同事达蒙·贝雷斯 (Damon Beres) 在 5 月份的时事通讯中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/05/altman-hearing-ai-existential-risk/674096/">所说</a>，用模糊的、存在主义的术语讨论这些技术“实际上让奥特曼和其他讨论人工智能未来的人能够避开我们已经从该技术中看到的一些日常影响。”人工智能现在确实正在产生非常现实的影响：聊天工具正在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/19/business/call-center-workers-battle-with-ai.html">侵蚀工作岗位</a>并重塑大学课堂。<br><br>达蒙补充说，通过要求监管，这些公司的负责人可以巧妙地将球交给立法者。 （如果国会需要很长时间才能通过法律，那么，至少业界已经尝试过！）批评者指出，奥特曼的监管理念之一——一个监督人工智能行业的新机构——可能需要几十年的时间才能建立。在这几十年里，人工智能可能会变得<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/06/ai-regulation-sam-altman-bill-gates/674278/">无处不在</a>。其他人指出，在建议国会通过一项法律，要求<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/05/19/podcasts/hard-fork-altman-yoel-roth.html?showTranscript=1">人工智能公司获得超过一定能力运营的许可证时</a>，像 OpenAI 这样的大公司可以巩固自己的地位，同时可能使小公司更难竞争。<br><br>科技行业可能已经从 2010 年代末的公关灾难中吸取了教训。领导人并没有像马克·扎克伯格在剑桥分析公司惨败后那样在惨败发生后作证，而是最近与华盛顿接触并<i>要求</i>监管。例如，萨姆·班克曼·弗里德 (Sam Bankman-Fried) 在 FTX 倒闭之前，通过讨好华盛顿并表现出致力于严格监管的态度，成功地支撑了自己的形象。经过多年游说反对监管，Facebook 近年来开始<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-17/facebook-needs-regulation-to-win-user-trust-zuckerberg-says?sref=B3uFyqJT">提出要求</a>。<br><br>人们很容易对自我设置的护栏感到愤世嫉俗，并认为它们是无用的。但周五的承诺承认还有很多工作要做，而激烈的行业竞争对手在这一事实上的一致表明，至少，完全绕过政府的护栏不再是好的公关。旧的做事方式不再那么令人愉快。不过，就目前而言，企业可能会继续尝试双管齐下。正如一位专家告诉马泰奥的那样，“你必须想知道：<i>如果你认为这如此危险，为什么还要建造它？</i> ”<br><br><b>相关</b>：<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/sam-altman-openai-chatgpt-gpt-4/674764/">山姆·奥特曼知道他在创造什么吗？</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/06/ai-regulation-sam-altman-bill-gates/674278/">人工智能厄运论是一个诱饵。</a></li><strong>今日新闻</strong><br><br><li>经过数月的抗议和拜登政府反复发出警告后，以色列立法者<a href="http://apnews.com/article/netanyahu-israel-hospital-judicial-overhaul-protests-closures-fb595629e7033ee34d246ee9a367c4d4">批准了</a>旨在削弱该国最高法院的立法计划的第一部分。</li><li>埃隆·马斯克<a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/twitter-rebrands-x-elon-musk-loses-iconic-bird-logo-rcna95880">将 Twitter 重新命名为“X”</a> ，取代了之前的蓝鸟标志。</li><li>俄罗斯无人机在袭击主要出口路线多瑙河沿岸的<a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-66289136">乌克兰港口</a>时摧毁了粮食基础设施。</li><strong>晚读</strong><br><br>美国的企业悲剧<br><br><em>凯特琳·弗拉纳根</em><br><br><p>我是加州葡萄罢工中的一名儿童兵，我的劳动是在伯克利的沙特克大道合作社外进行的。当时我大约七八岁，在联合农场工人的桌子旁摇晃装满硬币的福杰斯咖啡罐，我母亲每周有两到三个下午驻守在那里。我的大部分工作都是和她一起做的，但每小时有几次我会做儿童兵一直做的事情：以只有很小的人才能做的事情来服务。我会走到停车场，在汽车之间溜走，以确保没有人在不捐赠一些硬币或签署请愿书的情况下逃跑。我会突然出现在驾驶员侧的窗户旁边，使罐子发出剧烈的嘎嘎声。我不是吉米·霍法，但我也没有玩任何游戏。</p><p>我的父母是老派左翼分子，出生于 20 年代，是大萧条时期的孩子。他们永远不会越过纠察线，不会不参加抵制活动，不会在罢工者拿不到薪水时忽视他们对金钱的需求。我的父母永远不会说贫穷是因为缺乏智力或努力造成的。我们不是一个宗教家庭（至少可以这么说），但我有一个教义问答：一个工人是无能为力的；一个工人是无能为力的；一个工人是无能为力的。许多工人可以让一家公司屈服。</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/american-consumer-boycotts-bud-light-target/674745/">阅读全文。</a><br><br><b>更多来自<em>大西洋月刊</em></b><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/us-economy-labor-market-inflation-housing/674790/">选错公寓的问题</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/elder-senior-citizen-scams-fraud-exploitation/674793/">老年人如何被骗</a></li><b>文化突破</b><br><br><b>读。</b> 《 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/a-poem-by-janelle-tan-claude-glass-as-night-song/674800/">克劳德·格拉斯饰演夜歌</a>》，珍妮尔·谭的新诗。<br><br> “我希望你的胸口在我的胸口跳动，/所以我不能看着你。”<br><br><b>手表。</b><i>奥本海默</i>（现在在剧院）无处不在——包括在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-nuclear-bomb-anxiety-nightmares/674795/">人们的噩梦</a>中。<b> </b><br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/free-daily-crossword-puzzle/">玩我们的每日填字游戏。</a><br><br><strong>聚苯乙烯</strong><br><br>说到新技术恐慌，我的同事雅各布·斯特恩（Jacob Stern）写了一篇有趣而引人入胜的文章，讲述了人们对…… <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/power-point-evil-tufte-history/674797/">PowerPoint</a>的最初反应？显然，2003 年，一些人发现幻灯片技术是险恶的。雅各布描述了“一种现在几乎完全被遗忘的最高级别的技术恐慌：人们相信 PowerPoint——Office 软件套件中最令人疲惫的成员，催眠会议的通用转喻——可能是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wired.com/2003/09/ppt2/">邪恶的</a>。”我已经很多年没有制作 PowerPoint 了（快速浏览一下我的文件表明，我最后一次尝试幻灯片放映是在 2020 年我姐姐毕业之前，我发现一个文件只有一张幻灯片，用 Arial 字体写着“干得好，安妮”，另一个文件上有她和家里的狗的照片）。我几乎从来没有想到过 PowerPoint，所以读到人们惊慌失措地使用 PowerPoint 的经历是很有趣的。时代多么变化啊！<br><br> — 洛拉<br><br><i>Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</i><br><br><em>当您使用本新闻通讯中的链接购买书籍时，我们会收到佣金。感谢您对大西洋月刊的支持</em><em>。</em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 22:56:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/ai-companies-openai-voluntary-safeguards/674812/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/ai-companies-openai-voluntary-safeguards/674812/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Perfect Service to Make Everyone at the Airport Hate You]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The identification company Clear allows travelers to pay to cut in line. But you can&#39;t buy your way out of inconvenience at America&#39;s airports. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/DSDlBsG5CyRsUwUXoE4UHFRmw08=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/clear_horiz_illo_final/original.jpg" alt="红地毯通向 TSA 人体扫描仪" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Ben Kothe / The Atlantic.资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure> With sincere apologies, I need to ask you to imagine yourself arriving at the airport. Freshly expelled from whatever mode of transport brought you there, you are probably at least a little bit harried. Maybe you&#39;re running late or you&#39;re wrangling small children. Maybe you are weighed down by an overstuffed tote bag and a roll-aboard that could burst at any moment because you are opposed in principle to paying $50 to check a bag. The stink of anxiety sweat has begun to emanate from your person.<br><br> Waiting for you once you enter is the center of much airport melodrama: the TSA line. What you will encounter there is anyone&#39;s guess. You might hand over your ID to an agent and swing your bag onto the luggage scanner&#39;s belt near instantly, or hundreds of people might be in line in front of you. Can your laptop go in the same bin as your purse? Is your cardigan a shirt that you can continue wearing, or is it a jacket that needs to be removed? You&#39;ll find out when you find out, usually when someone with a badge yells at you.<br><br> Travel can be one of life&#39;s great joys, but the airport is, at its absolute best, a necessary obstacle to the eventual reward of visiting loved ones or experiencing a new place. At worst, it&#39;s a “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/02/laguardia-airport-redevelopment-american-infrastructure-lesson/673015/">ghastly purgatory</a> ,” in the words of my colleague Ian Bogost, riven with long waits, bad food, surprise fees, cramped quarters, spontaneous schedule changes, and lots of people acting like absolute unsocialized freaks. All of this chaos is subject to strict surveillance and regulation, and almost everything that happens once you enter an airport is out of your control.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2019/05/psychological-reason-people-are-late-airport/590500/">Read: There are two types of airport people</a><br><br> But what if you could wrest some of that control back? That&#39;s the promise behind Clear, whose employees you&#39;ve likely encountered in the past few years while flying: They&#39;re the smiling faces in neat checked shirts standing in front of a bank of sleek white consoles. They&#39;re friendlier than most TSA agents, and they&#39;ve got a deal to offer you: Fork over your ID, let them scan your eyeballs, pay nothing today, and they&#39;ll whisk you to the front of the line. Even if you&#39;ve never taken the bait yourself, you&#39;ve probably seen Clear employees pick off a few late-arriving travelers from the back of the line you&#39;re already waiting in. Maybe you&#39;ve even had the service&#39;s subscribers inserted in front of you just as it was your turn to pass through the checkpoint, violating a rule of civil society so basic that the average preschooler knows it: Cutting in line is wrong, and the people who have waited the longest should go next.<br><br> Clear is a strange phenomenon. It is in some ways similar to—and operates alongside—TSA PreCheck, the federal government&#39;s own paid-clearance service that ferries travelers more efficiently through airport screening. But unlike PreCheck, it&#39;s an independent, private company, woven into airports&#39; disorienting economy along with Hudson News and Dunkin&#39;. At its core, Clear is a biometric-data company, and the dismal experience of getting on an airplane has helped it do what few biometrics start-ups have managed to do: persuade millions of eager consumers to hand over their personal information and an annual fee. Lots of those start-ups aspire to turn your index finger or eyeball into an ID or a credit card, among other things, but Clear may be the one that&#39;s gotten closest to making that tech-industry dream a reality.<br><br> Clear is something else too. The service exists because American air travel is a needlessly punishing process, and navigating security is one of its worst bottlenecks. The enormous, intractable hassle of the airport has proved to be fertile ground for private-sector services designed to make the process of getting on a plane marginally more bearable. As travel rates surge, the airport, already heavily mediated by private-sector perks for high-spenders, has only become more stuffed with premium services and elite conveniences. When everything is a perk, what&#39;s left of the public good?<br><br> Like many things about contemporary American air travel, Clear&#39;s presence in airports is an indirect result of 9/11. Its predecessor, Verified Identity Pass, or VIP, was founded in the aftermath of the attacks, when the federal government was looking for companies that could expedite security procedures for people who flew a lot and were regarded as a low security risk, such as business travelers. VIP&#39;s signature product—confusingly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://archive.epic.org/privacy/airtravel/clear/">also called Clear</a> —gathered about 200,000 clients before the company filed for bankruptcy, in 2009. At that point, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://onezero.medium.com/clear-conquered-u-s-airports-now-it-wants-to-own-your-entire-digital-identity-15d61076e44d">according to a 2020 story on Clear</a> by the journalist Dave Gershgorn, it was bought by a duo of former hedge-fund managers who envisioned a life beyond government contracting for their new service.<br><br> VIP was rebranded to Clear, and the company, which had previously issued express-pass cards to its members, pivoted to biometrics. To sign up for Clear&#39;s marquee offering, Clear Plus, the company scans your irises and fingerprints, verifies your identity, and charges a $189-a-year fee after the initial free month for people who sign up at the airport. For that price, you get escorted to the front of the security line at the 52 North American airports where the company currently operates. If you have both Clear and TSA PreCheck, the service puts you at the front of the PreCheck line, so you can also keep your shoes on.<br><br> For anyone who doesn&#39;t have Clear Plus, the sales pitches and line-cutting can be pretty annoying. Clear&#39;s argument is that its services help security run more smoothly for all travelers. In an email, a company spokesperson, Annabel Walsh, described Clear as a “force multiplier” for airport efficiency: Travelers who get verified via Clear don&#39;t need to have their IDs checked by TSA, which frees up agents to check others. Airports also permit Clear salespeople to pull double duty by answering questions for travelers, Walsh told me. This appears to have upsides for both the company and the airport: Low pay and difficult work make attracting and retaining airport staff a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/business/economy/airports-have-always-had-trouble-attracting-workers-expect-longer-lines-n1272540">constant struggle</a> , so Clear salespeople can theoretically fill in some customer-assistance gaps while also finding solid opportunities to pitch their product. When someone signs up, the airport gets a cut of their subscription fee, which, according to Gershgorn&#39;s investigation, can add up to millions of dollars a year. (Walsh did not confirm this amount when asked.)<br><br> Walsh told me that Clear&#39;s programs currently have 16 million members. Not all of them pay for the line-jumping ease of Clear Plus: The company offers free programs—including one that allows you to reserve a time to go through security at some airports, and another that provides an express lane to get into some stadiums and arenas—that anyone can use after downloading a free app and uploading a selfie. Meanwhile, many of Clear Plus&#39;s members join because the program has become a common feature in the elite tiers of consumer-loyalty programs. Delta and United, which have both invested in Clear, will cover all or part of the Clear Plus fee for frequent fliers, and American Express Platinum cardholders get a full statement credit for a solo membership. Although Walsh adamantly opposed the idea that Clear could be regarded as a <em>perk</em> instead of a <em>vital bit of security infrastructure</em> , it is indeed a pretty popular perk.<br><br> As Clear&#39;s move into stadiums and arenas suggests, the company&#39;s biggest ambitions span beyond air travel. Clear wants to expand its verification technologies into other domains of modern life that require waiting and fumbling around for identification. In particular, the company has designs on the health-care industry. Earlier in the pandemic, Clear developed a free service to verify members&#39; vaccination status and recent test results, and Walsh told me that in the future, Clear verification could be used to do things like unlock a patient&#39;s medical records, insurance card, and co-pay; the company is currently working on such a system with University of Miami Health. Clear, or a company like it, could one day function as a one-stop shop for your personal identity, a middleman between you and the government, your doctor, your professional licensing, and potentially much more. Instead of getting your insurance card out of your wallet or tapping your phone against a card reader to use Apple Pay, all of it would be contained within your fingerprint.<br><br> For whatever company that manages to make all of this a widely adopted reality, there is significant upside to be gained—not only in contracting for the services themselves and selling memberships to use them, but potentially also in the treasure trove of data collected. The minute details of your travel habits, medical history, event attendance, and purchases, all compiled into a single user profile with a verified identity, can be worth a lot of money. Clear is adamant that the company does not and will not sell or give any user data to third parties without permission from individual users. Even so, as Gershgorn points out, many major tech companies that take in massive amounts of revenue through advertisements do not technically sell user data to third parties either. Facebook, for instance, sells access to pools of consumers who meet an advertiser&#39;s desired demographic criteria through ad targeting.<br><br> Walsh told me that the only thing Clear uses member data for is to provide services to its members, and that it does not monetize its data through promotional targeting. The <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.clearme.com/privacy-policy">privacy policy</a> that governs Clear&#39;s services would at least seem to allow it, however. The policy stipulates that Clear may use everything but its biometric and health data to conduct marketing and consumer research, contact members about products and services from its marketing partners, and “offer our consumers products or services we believe may be of interest to them.” Walsh defended the policy, saying it “allows Clear to keep our members informed about new Clear services, and helps us prioritize what new services to build for our members.”<br><br> Feeling a little creeped out by Clear is easy, no matter how widely its employees smile at you as you slog toward your gate. There are many arguments against data collection, but the main one is pretty simple: The more companies know about you, the easier it becomes for them to manipulate you in weak moments or part you from your money. If you&#39;ve ever been buried under ads about wedding vendors or baby products after a little light googling that might imply you&#39;re newly engaged or pregnant, then you know how readily these unseen forces can discern the most intimate details of your life. Wariness of these practices is a big reason so many biometrics companies have a difficult time finding eager customers. If the value proposition is the ability to pay with your fingerprint in exchange for all of your personal data, you might rightly decide that it&#39;s not that hard to tap a credit card or your phone against a reader.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/06/airport-bars-drinking-morning/674322/">Read: It&#39;s 5 am somewhere</a><br><br> That said, commercial life in America has shown time and again that people tend to be happy to relinquish all kinds of personal information for the right amount of convenience. The fact that Clear has amassed millions of members makes a fairly convincing case that traversing American airport security is simply <em>that grim</em> ; people are ready to skip the line, fingerprints be damned. In this regard, Clear&#39;s close ties with consumer-loyalty programs makes particular sense. Loyalty programs are one of the most popular ways to make personal-data gathering palatable to the general public: You agree to have your behavior tracked under a unique identifier such as a frequent-flier number, then you get discounts or conveniences or special perks. Many people might not even realize the bargain they&#39;re making, but many others seem perfectly fine with it. If you can save a little on your grocery bill, who cares if Kroger has a slightly easier time tracking what you&#39;ve purchased?<br><br> Skepticism, in other words, might not be a real issue for Clear. Instead, their biggest hurdle might actually be the opposite: a rush for any services that attempt to game the airport&#39;s system. By finding advantage in the chaos of American airline travel, Clear has entered an arms race that might not be winnable, for it or anyone else. The nature of the company&#39;s business means that it always has to remain a step ahead of the airport crowd. If that crowd catches up, Clear will be overwhelmed by the infrastructural flaws on top of which it&#39;s built—a phenomenon that only helps generate more new private-sector services to make things a little less bad for the people who fly the most.<br><br> Gary Leff, an airline-industry expert and the founder of the travel website View From the Wing, told me that for years, airline watchers have been asking the TSA to make simple changes that they argue would speed up the screening process without compromising safety—ending the war on carry-on liquids, allowing small scissors, letting people keep their shoes on and leave their laptops in their bags. These changes would address the bottlenecks where they&#39;re most likely to happen: not at the ID checkpoint from which Clear Plus exempts its members, but from the part immediately after that, where you and all your belongings get a visual once-over. They&#39;d also be free and benefit all travelers. TSA has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2011/09/07/140240633/for-now-shoes-still-come-off-at-airport-security">maintained</a> that the procedures in place are <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.fodors.com/news/news/will-the-u-s-change-its-3-1-1-liquid-rule-on-flights">essential</a> for safety. These kinds of changes tend to become political footballs, which makes it difficult to do anything that could be construed as too permissive. It&#39;s even more difficult, according to Leff, to get the kinds of changes that would make the biggest difference in your experience at the airport—namely, more funding for the woefully understaffed Federal Aviation Administration and for capital improvements at America&#39;s aging airports.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/02/laguardia-airport-redevelopment-american-infrastructure-lesson/673015/">Read: America built an actually good airport</a><br><br> So instead, occasional fliers suffer through unpredictable security lines, and frequent travelers arbitrage airline and credit-card perks. Their frustration is legible in the popularity of TSA PreCheck, which costs $78 for a five-year membership: By early 2022, the number of members in the Department of Homeland Security&#39;s Trusted Traveler programs (most of whom are PreCheck users) had increased 44 percent from before the pandemic, to nearly 30 million people, according to the travel site<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thepointsguy.com/news/tsa-precheck-more-members/"><em>The Points Guy</em></a> . That popularity is also something of an Achilles heel. The program&#39;s members may have their own line, but it&#39;s subject to the same issues of understaffing and aging infrastructure as all the others, and the more people use the program, the more the PreCheck line looks like the regular one.<br><br> The thing about perks is that people pursue them. Catering to people who fly constantly has a way of making a service crowded, because, well, those people are at the airport all the time. As Clear has grown, it&#39;s encountered some of the same issues as PreCheck. Namely, you might find yourself once again having to wait, this time to have your iris or fingertip scanned. Leff, who told me he&#39;s a longtime, mostly satisfied Clear member, said that since travel volume has picked up again after the height of the pandemic, he sometimes just gets his ID out and goes to the PreCheck line because it looks like it&#39;ll be faster than waiting to check in with Clear. (Walsh told me that on average, Clear members wait for less than five minutes.)<br><br> Infrastructural bottlenecks like TSA can&#39;t be solved with private-sector services, because all you&#39;re really doing is temporarily outrunning the crowd. Eventually, even with an expensive service like Clear, too many people will catch up, and the problem underlying it all still won&#39;t be fixed. “The more people who have access to it, the longer the lines you&#39;re going to face,” Leff said. “At some level, it&#39;s potentially just a temporary reprieve.”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 20:55:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/clear-airport-security-lines-tsa-infrastructure/674809/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/clear-airport-security-lines-tsa-infrastructure/674809/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Ticks Are Winning]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>他们的唾液是一种秘密武器。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/UrzkYZixYduVStPocLpnoGefvsE=/0x0:1767x994/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1036497574/original.jpg" alt="透过绿叶背面看到的蜱虫轮廓，叶脉可见" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>帕特里克·普勒尔/图片联盟/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>我活了三十多年，从来没有被蜱虫咬过。事实上，这可能是一个谎言，我无法确定。因为尽管蜱虫有鱼叉状的口器，尽管某些种类的蜱虫可以吸吮<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7355616/">长达两周的时间</a>，尽管有些蜱虫吸食的血液足以使体重膨胀 100 倍，但它们的叮咬却谨慎得令人不安。德克萨斯农工大学蜱虫研究员阿德拉·奥利瓦·查韦斯 (Adela Oliva Chavez) 表示，“小时候，我身上有数百只蜱虫”，其中至少有几只会咬人。然而她永远不会注意到，直到她姨妈把它们从她的皮肤上摘下来。<br><br>蜱虫隐形背后的秘密是蜱虫的<em>唾液</em>——一种奇怪的、滑溜的、多面的液体，没有生物同类<em>。</em>它可以让害虫的叮咬处保持奇异的瘙痒和疼痛，并让它们不受宿主免疫力的影响而不受阻碍地进食。随着气候变化重塑世界，唾液也帮助蜱虫进入新的栖息地和宿主，并带来许多致命的病毒、细菌和寄生虫。<br><br>尽管蜱虫非常依赖血液，但它们几乎从不吃东西。在它们有时长达数年的生命周期中，它们在每个阶段可能只进食一次：幼虫、若虫和成虫。这意味着， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2019/07/the-marvels-of-tick-saliva/594652/">正如我的同事莎拉·张曾经写道的那样，每顿饭都必须非常重要。</a>与蚊子和其他吸血昆虫可以轻易逃脱的不同，蜱虫必须在肉上停留数天甚至数周——这是一场漫长的盛宴，需要它们像临时肢体一样移植到宿主的身体上。<br><br>在整个过程中，唾液是关键。当蜱虫第一次叮咬时，它的唾液会在伤口上涂上一种胶状物质，<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30459085/">将其嘴固定在适当的位置</a>。一旦安全，蜱虫就会部署<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fcimb.2017.00281/full">一系列唾液传播的化合物</a>，扩张宿主的血管，同时与通常会促使伤口凝结、愈合或因疼痛或瘙痒而刺痛的身体化合物作斗争。在大多数情况下，这种外来分子的攻击会立即集结人体的免疫骑兵。但蜱虫也有解决方法。它们的唾液具有抗炎和镇痛作用；它可以禁用细胞之间相互发送的警报，从而防止它们协调攻击。唾液甚至可以对免疫细胞进行重新编程，使它们永远无法完成发育或接收到在现场收集所需的线索。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2019/02/ticks-can-take-down-800-pound-moose/583189/">阅读：气候变化进入吸血阶段</a><br><br>所有这些策略还可以为蜱虫从一个宿主吞下然后沉积到下一个宿主的细菌、病毒和寄生虫<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fcimb.2021.816547/full">提供便利</a>。当蜱虫的唾液突破皮肤屏障并保持免疫系统受到控制时，病原体所要做的就是随之而来。生物技术初创公司 Arcadia Science 的首席执行官 Seemay Chou 表示：“蜱虫的唾液就像一辆豪华车辆，将它们运送到感染部位并铺上红地毯。”研究表明，多种病原体在唾液的推动下会 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10118219/">增强</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://journals.asm.org/doi/10.1128/jvi.01056-15">感染力</a>，更有效地扩散到新被咬伤宿主的皮肤中。伯氏疏螺旋体<em>（Borrelia burgdorferi）</em>是引起莱姆病的细菌，它甚至会将<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8001052/">蜱虫唾液的一部分像斗篷一样涂在自己身上</a>，基本上使自己<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4306560/">对身体防御来说不可见</a>。蜱虫的传染性物质甚至可能会互相怂恿：纽约州北部医科大学的 Saravanan Thangamani 发现证据表明，<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mdpi.com/1999-4915/14/7/1584">同时携带<em>伯氏疏螺旋体</em>和波瓦桑病毒的</a>蜱虫最终可能会将<em>更多</em>的后者注入新伤口中。<br><br>蜱虫向人类及其牲畜传播的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6024845/">病原体已经比任何其他昆虫或蜘蛛都多</a>。蜱虫带来的风险可能只会<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/10.1146/annurev-ento-052720-094533">越来越大</a>，因为气温升高和人类对野生动物的干扰使它们能够扩大其地理范围并渗透到新的宿主。在北美，孤星蜱虫和黑腿蜱虫正在精心策划向北进入加拿大。与此同时，蜱虫携带感染的<em>比例</em>也在增加，坦加马尼告诉我，几十年来，世界多个地区的莱姆病和蜱传脑炎病例数一直在稳步上升。随着寒冷季节的缩短，一年中蜱虫叮咬的时期（通常是最温暖的月份）也在扩大。 “很多很多地方都充满了蜱虫，”密歇根州立大学昆虫学家 Jean Tsao 说。 “而且他们会得到更多。”<br><br>这有助于许多蜱虫对它们携带或叮咬的对象并不挑剔。一些物种在进入新的地方时，在过去几年中感染了新的病原体——波旁病毒、中心地带病毒——这对我们构成了额外的威胁。许多蜱类对其宿主也相对不加区别：在其一生中，一只鹿蜱可能“非常愉快地以爬行动物、禽类和鸟类为食”，牛津大学病毒学家兼蜱虫研究员帕特·纳托尔说。它们的唾液非常复杂，可以定制以依次抵消每个物种的防御。奥利瓦·查韦斯 (Oliva Chavez) 告诉我，将蜱虫从兔子身上转移到人或狗身上，它会注意到并<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fcimb.2017.00517/full">调整其唾液</a>，确切地说是为了适应味道。<br><br>对抗莱姆病和其他蜱传疾病的疫苗长期以来一直在开发中。但许多研究人员认为，更有效的策略是追捕蜱虫本身，田纳西大学诺克斯维尔分校的蜱虫生物学家吉里什·尼拉坎塔 (Girish Neelakanta) 表示，这种策略充其量只能“同时阻止多种病原体的传播”。抗蜱免疫是可能的：研究记录了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34074602/">豚鼠、牛、兔子、山羊和狗</a>在被反复叮咬后，对蜘蛛类动物产生了持续的防御能力，甚至可以帮助动物立即发现叮咬并清除害虫的反应。<br><br>但吐口水对于身体防御来说是一个难以击中的目标。该物质不仅仅会关闭免疫反应。它还不断地重新调整自身，以便能够不断逃避宿主的防御——每隔几个小时一次，速度比大多数免疫系统的跟踪速度都要快。当身体准备好攻击一种唾液成分时，蜱虫几乎肯定已经将其换成了另一种成分。耶鲁大学蜱虫研究员苏卡尼娅·纳拉西姆汉 (Sukanya Narasimhan) 表示：“这是蜱虫正在玩的游戏，一种捉住我的游戏。” Narasimhan 认为，为了战胜蜱虫的伎俩，关键是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://medicine.yale.edu/profile/sukanya-narasimhan/?tab=research">开发一种疫苗</a>，“一旦蜱虫附着，”就能触发人体对蜱虫叮咬做出<em>快速</em>反应，最好是针对唾液的第一个成分。<br><br>当蜱虫继续占据统治地位时，我们很难不对它们的勇气产生至少一些勉强的尊重。一些科学家甚至认为研究或<em>模仿</em>它们的唾液可能会带来<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fphys.2019.00812/full">其他突破</a>。模仿唾液的免疫抑制倾向可能有助于治疗哮喘，或用于辅助器官移植的药物；模仿其抗凝特性可以帮助防止危及生命的血栓。一些蜱唾液成分甚至促使人们研究其作为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2214750018305468?via%3Dihub">癌症</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s13318-018-0500-z">治疗</a>的潜力。毕竟，蜱虫研究哺乳动物身体已有数百万年之久，所有这些都是为了找到借口。在他们的指导下，Arcadia Science 首席执行官周希望更多地了解驱动瘙痒冲动的分子途径。<br><br><br>然而，蜱虫并不是无敌的，现在一些相同的全球变化使它们更容易进入新的栖息地，最终可能会阻碍它们的进步。它们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://time.com/6262408/climate-change-lyme-disease-ticks/">已经</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://academic.oup.com/jme/article/58/4/1536/5942051">开始逃离地球上</a>那些变得太热、太潮湿、太泛滥、被野火夷为平地的地区，它们或它们喜欢的寄主无法生存，其中包括<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0168723">美国南部的某些荒凉地区</a>。价格变动的下降可能对我们有利。但这也可能是全球灾难日益严重的一个症状。坦加马尼告诉我，蜱虫无疑“将继续适应”。然而，它们也有其局限性——比我们的局限性更远，但也没有那么远。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 14:36:37 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/tick-bite-saliva-infection-spread/674804/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/tick-bite-saliva-infection-spread/674804/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Does Sam Altman Know What He’s Creating?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> OpenAI 首席执行官雄心勃勃、独创性、令人敬畏的追求，创造一种新的智能形式<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/4bX2g65va3VcwJO-qx1nrFJwQrg=/13x50:1028x1318/648x810/media/img/2023/07/20/WEL_Andersen_OpenAiBrain-1/original.png" alt="紫色背景下具有向不同方向拉伸的线状股的抽象大脑的插图" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>里卡多·雷伊插图</figcaption></figure>四月的<span class="smallcaps">一个星期一早上</span>，萨姆·奥尔特曼 (Sam Altman) 坐在 OpenAI 旧金山总部内，向我讲述了他的公司已经构建但永远不会发布的危险人工智能。他后来说，他的员工经常失眠，担心有一天他们可能会释放人工智能，而没有充分认识到它们的危险。他的脚后跟搭在转椅的边缘，看上去很放松​​。他的公司在 11 月<i>发布的</i>强大人工智能吸引了全世界的想象力，这在近代科技史上是前所未有的。有些人抱怨 ChatGPT 还不能做好，而另一些人则抱怨它可能预示的未来，但 Altman 并不担心；对他来说，这是一个胜利的时刻。<br><br>小剂量时，奥特曼的蓝色大眼睛会发出一束真诚的智力注意力，他似乎明白，大剂量时，它们的强度可能会令人不安。在这种情况下，他愿意冒这个险：他想让我知道，无论人工智能的最终风险是什么，他对于让 ChatGPT 进入这个世界都零后悔。相反，他认为这是一项伟大的公共服务。<br><br> “我们本可以在我们的大楼里再建造五年，”他说，“我们会得到一些令人瞠目结舌的东西。”但公众无法为随之而来的冲击波做好准备，他认为这种结果“非常难以想象”。奥特曼认为，人们需要时间来考虑这样一个想法：在它重塑从工作到人际关系的一切之前，我们可能很快就会与强大的新智能共享地球。 ChatGPT 是一种发送通知的方式。<br><br> 2015 年，Altman、Elon Musk 和几位著名的人工智能研究人员创立了 OpenAI，因为他们相信通用人工智能（比如典型的大学毕业生的智力能力）终于触手可及。他们想要实现这一目标，甚至更多：他们想要召唤一种超级智能到世界上，一种绝对优于任何人类的智能。尽管一家大型科技公司可能为了自己的目的而不顾一切地抢先到达那里，但他们希望安全地做到这一点，“<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://openai.com/blog/introducing-openai">以造福整个人类</a>。”他们将 OpenAI 构建为非营利组织，“不受产生财务回报的需要的限制”，并誓言透明地进行研究。没有人可以撤退到新墨西哥州沙漠中的绝密实验室。<br><br>多年来，公众对 OpenAI 的了解不多。据报道，奥特曼在 2019 年成为首席执行官时， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.semafor.com/article/03/24/2023/the-secret-history-of-elon-musk-sam-altman-and-openai">据说是在与马斯克发生权力斗争之后</a>，这几乎算不上是一个故事。 OpenAI 发表了论文，其中包括同年一篇关于新人工智能的论文。这引起了硅谷科技界的充分关注，但直到去年人们开始使用 ChatGPT 时，这项技术的潜力才为公众所认识。<br><br>现在为 ChatGPT 提供动力的引擎称为 GPT-4。奥特曼向我描述它是一种外星智慧。许多人看到它以断断续续的爆发和短暂的停顿来展开清晰的文章时也有同样的感觉，这些文章（故意）引起了实时的沉思。在成立的几个月里，它根据自己的风味组合理论<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/04/chatgpt-generative-ai-reliability-creativity-grocery-list/673759/">提出了新颖的鸡尾酒配方</a>；撰写了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/05/chatbot-cheating-college-campuses/674073/">无数的大学论文</a>，让教育工作者陷入绝望； <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/02/chatgpt-ai-technology-writing-poetry/673035/">写的诗风格多样</a>，有时写得很好，但总是很快；并通过了统一律师考试。它犯了事实错误，但它会迷人地承认错误。 Altman 仍然记得他第一次看到 GPT-4 编写复杂的计算机代码时的情景，而 GPT-4 并没有明确设计这种能力。 “这就像是，‘我们到了，’”他说。<br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/technology/chatgpt-sets-record-fastest-growing-user-base-analyst-note-2023-02-01/">根据 UBS 的一项研究</a>，ChatGPT 发布后九周内，其月用户数量估计已达到 1 亿，这可能使其成为当时历史上采用速度最快的消费产品。它的成功唤醒了科技界的加速主义者：美国和中国的大投资者和大公司迅速将数百亿美元投入到仿照 OpenAI 方法的研发中。预测网站 Metaculus 多年来一直在追踪预测者对通用人工智能何时到来的猜测。三年半前，预测的中位数是 2050 年左右；现在是 2050 年。最近一直徘徊在2026年左右。<br><br>我访问 OpenAI 是为了了解该公司超越科技巨头的技术，并了解如果有一天超级智能很快在该公司的一台云服务器中实现，这对人类文明可能意味着什么。从计算革命的最初阶段起，人工智能就被神话为一种注定会带来深刻断裂的技术。我们的文化已经产生了人工智能的整个想象，以这种或那种方式结束历史。有些是神一样的存在，在他们迎来无摩擦的丰富和美丽的永恒之前，他们会擦去每一滴眼泪，治愈病人并修复我们与地球的关系。其他人则将我们中除了少数精英之外的所有人都沦为零工农奴，或者将我们推向灭绝。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/06/ai-warfare-nuclear-weapons-strike/673780/">摘自2023年6月号：永远不要给人工智能核密码</a><br><br>奥特曼已经接受了最遥远的场景。 “当我还是个年轻的成年人时，”他说，“我有这种恐惧、焦虑......而且，老实说，也有 2% 的兴奋，因为我们将创造这个东西”，“它将远远超越我们”，“它将会消失，殖民宇宙，而人类将被留在太阳系。”<br><br> “作为自然保护区？”我问。<br><br> “完全正确，”他说。 “现在我觉得这太天真了。”<br><br>在美国和亚洲的几次谈话中，奥特曼用他令人兴奋的中西部语气阐述了他对人工智能未来的新愿景。他告诉我，人工智能革命将不同于以前的巨大技术变革，它将更像“一种新型社会”。他说，他和他的同事花了很多时间思考人工智能的社会影响，以及“另一边”的世界将会是什么样子。<br><br>但越聊，对方就越显得模糊。现年38岁的奥特曼是当今人工智能开发领域最有权势的人；他的观点、性格和选择可能对我们所有人的未来都非常重要，也许比美国总统的观点、性格和选择更重要。但他自己也承认，未来是不确定的，并且充满了严重的危险。奥特曼不知道人工智能将变得多么强大，也不知道它的崛起对普通人意味着什么，也不知道它是否会让人类面临危险。确切地说，我并不反对他——我认为没有人知道这一切将走向何方，除了我们正在快速走向那里，无论我们是否应该这样做。奥特曼说服了我。<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">OpenAI 的总部</span>位于 Mission 区一座四层楼的前工厂内，位于雾气缭绕的 Sutro 塔下方。从街道进入其大厅，您遇到的第一面墙被曼陀罗覆盖，曼陀罗是宇宙的精神代表，由电路、铜线和其他计算材料制成。左边，一扇安全门通向一个开放式迷宫，里面有漂亮的金色树林、优雅的瓷砖作品和亿万富翁别致的其他标志。植物无处不在，包括悬挂的蕨类植物和一系列令人印象深刻的超大盆景，每个盆景都有蹲伏的大猩猩大小。我在那里的时候，办公室里每天都挤满了人，不出所料，我没有看到任何看起来超过 50 岁的人。除了一个配有滑梯的两层图书馆外，这个空间看起来不太像一个研究实验室，因为正在建造的东西只存在于云端，至少目前是这样。它看起来更像是世界上最昂贵的西榆树。<br><br>一天早上，我会见了 OpenAI 的首席科学家 Ilya Sutskever。 37 岁的 Sutskever 有一种神秘主义者的感觉，有时甚至有些过失：去年，他声称 GPT-4 可能“有轻微意识” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://futurism.com/the-byte/openai-already-sentient">，引起了一场小规模的骚动</a>。他最初是作为多伦多大学名誉教授杰弗里·辛顿 (Geoffrey Hinton) 的明星学生而出名的，后者<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/05/01/technology/ai-google-chatbot-engineer-quits-hinton.html">今年春天从谷歌辞职</a>，以便能够更自由地谈论人工智能对人类的危险。<br><br> Hinton 有时被称为“人工智能教父”，因为他比大多数人更早掌握“深度学习”的力量。 20 世纪 80 年代，Hinton 完成博士学位后不久，该领域的进展几乎陷入停滞。高级研究人员仍在编写自上而下的人工智能系统：人工智能将使用一套详尽的连锁规则（关于语言、地质学或医学诊断原理）进行编程，希望有一天这种方法能够达到人类水平的认知。 Hinton 发现这些精心设计的规则集合非常挑剔并且是定制的。在一种称为神经网络的巧妙算法结构的帮助下，他教 Sutskever 将世界放在人工智能面前，就像把它放在一个小孩面前一样，这样它就可以自己发现现实的规则。<br><br>奥特曼将早期人工智能研究与教导人类婴儿进行了比较。但在 OpenAI 的最初几年，没有人知道他们是在训练婴儿，还是在追求一条极其昂贵的死胡同。<br><br> Sutskever 向我描述了一个美丽且像大脑一样的神经网络。有一次，他从我们坐的桌子上站起来，走近一块白板，打开了一支红色记号笔。他在黑板上画了一个粗略的神经网络，并解释说，其结构的天才在于它能够学习，而它的学习是由<i>预测</i>驱动的——有点像科学方法。神经元分层分布。例如，输入层接收数据块、一段文本或图像。神奇的事情发生在中间层（或“隐藏”层），它们处理数据块，以便输出层可以输出其预测。<br><br>想象一个已被编程为预测文本中的下一个单词的神经网络。它将预载大量可能的单词。但在接受训练之前，它还没有任何区分它们的经验，因此它的预测会很差劲。如果输入句子“星期三后的一天是……”，它的初始输出可能是“紫色”。神经网络之所以能够学习，是因为它的训练数据包含正确的预测，这意味着它可以对自己的输出进行评分。当它看到答案“紫色”和正确答案“星期四”之间的鸿沟时，它会相应地调整隐藏层中单词之间的连接。随着时间的推移，这些微小的调整会合并成一个语言的几何模型，从概念上代表单词之间的关系。一般来说，输入的句子越多，模型就越复杂，预测也越好。<br><br>这并不是说从第一个神经网络到 GPT-4 的类人智能的曙光的道路是容易的。奥特曼将早期人工智能研究与教导人类婴儿进行了比较。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/10/10/sam-altmans-manifest-destiny">2016 年，当 OpenAI 刚刚起步时，他告诉<i>《纽约客》</i> ：</a> “他们需要数年时间才能学习任何有趣的东西。” “如果人工智能研究人员正在开发一种算法，并且偶然发现了针对人类婴儿的算法，他们会觉得无聊，认为它不起作用，然后将其关闭。” OpenAI 的最初几年很艰难，部分原因是那里没有人知道他们是在训练婴儿还是在追求极其昂贵的死胡同。<br><br> “一切都不起作用，而谷歌拥有一切：所有的人才、所有的人员、所有的资金，”奥特曼告诉我。创始人投入了数百万美元创办了这家公司，但失败似乎确实有可能。 35 岁的总统格雷格·布罗克曼 (Greg Brockman) 告诉我，2017 年，他非常沮丧，开始举重作为补偿措施。他说，他不确定 OpenAI 能否撑过这一年，他希望“能在我的时间里展示一些东西”。<br><br>神经网络已经在做智能的事情，但尚不清楚其中哪一个可能会导致通用智能。 OpenAI 成立后不久，一款名为 AlphaGo 的人工智能<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2016/03/the-invisible-opponent/475611/">在围棋（一种比国际象棋复杂得多的游戏）中击败了李世石</a>，震惊了世界。被击败的世界冠军李将 AlphaGo 的棋步形容为“美丽”且“富有创意”。另一位顶级选手表示，他们永远不可能是人类孕育出来的。 OpenAI 尝试在<i>Dota 2</i>上训练人工智能，这是一款更加复杂的游戏，涉及森林、田野和堡垒的三维拼凑而成的多线奇幻战争。它最终<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/4/13/18309459/openai-five-dota-2-finals-ai-bot-competition-og-e-sports-the-international-champion">击败了最好的人类玩家</a>，但它的智能从未转化为其他环境。苏茨克维尔和他的同事们就像失望的父母一样，他们允许自己的孩子玩电子游戏数千个小时，这违背了他们更好的判断。<br><br> 2017 年，Sutskever 开始与 OpenAI 研究科学家 Alec Radford 进行一系列对话，Alec Radford 致力于自然语言处理。雷德福德通过在亚马逊评论语料库上训练神经网络，取得了诱人的结果。<br><br> ChatGPT 的内部工作原理（所有发生在 GPT-4 隐藏层中的神秘事物）对于任何人来说都过于复杂，无法理解，至少使用当前的工具是这样。如今，追踪模型（几乎肯定由数十亿个神经元组成）中发生的事情是没有希望的。但雷德福的模型足够简单，易于理解。当他查看其隐藏层时，他发现它专门使用了一个特殊的神经元来处理评论的<i>情绪</i>。神经网络之前已经做过情感分析，但它们必须被告知才能这样做，并且必须使用根据情感标记的数据进行特殊训练。这个功能是自己开发出来的。<br><br>作为预测每个单词中下一个字符的简单任务的副产品，雷德福的神经网络模拟了世界上更大的意义结构。苏茨克维尔想知道，受过更多样化语言数据训练的人是否可以绘制更多世界意义结构。如果它的隐藏层积累了足够的概念知识，也许它们甚至可以形成一种超级智能的学习核心模块。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">值得停下来</span>理解为什么语言是如此特殊的信息源。假设你是地球上突然出现的一种新智慧。你周围是地球的大气层、太阳和银河系，以及数千亿个其他星系，每一个星系都会释放出光波、声音振动和各种其他信息。语言与这些数据源不同。它不是像光或声音这样的直接物理信号。但由于它几乎编码了人类在这个更大的世界中发现的所有模式，因此它的信息异常密集。从每个字节的角度来看，它是我们所知道的最有效的数据之一，任何试图了解世界的新智能都希望吸收尽可能多的数据。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/06/henry-kissinger-ai-could-mean-the-end-of-human-history/559124/">摘自 2018 年 6 月号：亨利·A·基辛格 (Henry A. Kissinger) 谈人类社会如何对人工智能的崛起毫无准备</a><br><br>苏茨克维尔告诉雷德福德，要考虑的不仅仅是亚马逊评论。他说，他们应该在世界上最大、最多样化的数据源：互联网上训练人工智能。在 2017 年初，使用现有的神经网络架构，这是不切实际的；这需要数年时间。但当年 6 月，Sutskever 在 Google Brain 的前同事发表了一篇关于名为 Transformer 的新神经网络架构的工作论文。它可以训练得更快，部分原因是并行吸收大量数据。 “第二天，当论文发表时，我们说，‘就是这样，’”苏茨克维尔告诉我。 “‘它给了我们想要的一切。’ ”<br><br>一年后，即 2018 年 6 月，OpenAI 发布了 GPT，这是一个经过 7000 多本书训练的 Transformer 模型。 GPT 并不是从<i>《See Spot Run》</i>这样的基础书籍开始，一直到普鲁斯特。连书都没读完。它同时吸收了其中的随机块。想象一下，一群拥有共同思想的学生在图书馆里疯狂奔跑，每个人从书架上撕下一本书，快速阅读随机的短文，将其放回去，然后跑去拿另一本。他们边走边预测一个又一个字，磨砺他们集体思维的语言本能，直到几周后，他们终于读完了每一本书。<br><br> GPT 在它读取的所有段落中发现了许多模式。你可以告诉它完成一个句子。你也可以问它一个问题，因为像 ChatGPT 一样，它的预测模型知道问题后面通常有答案。尽管如此，它还是很糟糕，更多的是概念证明，而不是超级智能的预兆。四个月后，谷歌发布了 BERT，这是一种更强大的语言模型，并得到了更好的报道。但那时，OpenAI 已经在超过 800 万个网页的数据集上训练了一个新模型，每个网页都在 Reddit 上达到了点赞的最低阈值——这不是最严格的过滤器，但也许比没有过滤器要好。<br><br> Sutskever 不确定 GPT-2 在吸收了人类读者需要几个世纪才能吸收的文本正文后会有多强大。他记得在训练结束后就开始玩它，并对原始模型的语言翻译能力感到惊讶。 GPT-2 没有像谷歌翻译那样接受过使用配对语言样本或任何其他数字罗塞塔石碑进行翻译的训练，但它似乎能够理解一种语言与另一种语言的关系。人工智能已经发展出了一种其创造者无法想象的新兴能力。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">其他大大小小的人工智能实验室的研究人员</span>都对 GPT-2 比 GPT 先进得多感到惊讶。谷歌、Meta 和其他公司很快开始训练更大的语言模型。 Altman 是圣路易斯人，斯坦福大学辍学生，连续创业者，此前曾领导过硅谷卓越的初创企业加速器 Y Combinator；他见过很多拥有好创意的年轻公司被老牌公司压垮。为了筹集资金，OpenAI 增加了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://openai.com/blog/openai-lp">一个营利性部门</a>，该部门目前占该组织员工总数的 99% 以上。 （马斯克当时已离开公司董事会，他将<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?t=243&amp;v=bWr-DA5Wjfw&amp;feature=youtu.be">此举比作</a>将雨林保护组织转变为木材公司。）微软不久后投资了 10 亿美元，据报道此后又投资了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/01/23/business/microsoft-chatgpt-artificial-intelligence.html">120 亿美元</a>。 OpenAI 表示，初始投资者的回报将上限为原始投资价值的 100 倍，任何超额部分都将用于教育或其他旨在造福人类的举措，但该公司并未证实微软的上限。<br><br> Altman 和 OpenAI 的其他领导人似乎充满信心，认为重组不会干扰公司的使命，实际上只会加速其完成。奥特曼对这些问题往往持乐观态度。在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://greylock.com/greymatter/sam-altman-ai-for-the-next-era/">去年的一次问答</a>中，他承认人工智能对社会来说可能“非常可怕”，并表示我们必须针对最坏的可能性做好计划。但如果你这样做，他说，“你可能会在情感上感觉到我们将到达美好的未来，并尽你所能地努力工作以实现这一目标。”<br><br>至于公司结构和融资的其他变化，他告诉我，他在上市时划定了界限。他说：“有人曾经告诉我一件令人难忘的事情，那就是你永远不应该将公司的控制权交给华尔街的傻瓜，”但他会为公司成功实现其使命“不惜一切代价”筹集资金。<br><br>无论 OpenAI 是否感受到季度收益报告的压力，该公司现在都发现自己正在与科技领域最大、最强大的企业集团展开一场竞赛，以训练规模和复杂性不断增加的模型，并为投资者将其商业化。今年早些时候，马斯克成立了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/martineparis/2023/04/16/elon-musk-launches-xai-to-fight-chatgpt-woke-ai-with-twitter-data/?sh=4c2ff9fd51f8">自己的人工智能实验室</a>——xAI——与 OpenAI 竞争。 （“埃隆是一个超级敏锐的家伙，”当我向奥特曼询问有关该公司的情况时，他外交地说道。“我认为他会在那里做得很好。”）与此同时，亚马逊正在使用比过去更大的语言模型来改进 Alexa。<br><br>所有这些公司都在追逐高端 GPU——为训练大型神经网络的超级计算机提供动力的处理器。马斯克表示，它们现在“比毒品更难获得”。即使 GPU 稀缺，近年来最大规模的人工智能训练规模大约每六个月就会翻一番。<br><br>正如它们的创造者经常提醒我们的那样，最大的人工智能模型都有在训练中突然出现意想不到的能力的记录。<br><br>目前还没有人超越 OpenAI，后者全力投入 GPT-4。 OpenAI 总裁布罗克曼 (Brockman) 告诉我，只有少数人致力于公司前两个大型语言模型的开发。 GPT-4的开发涉及超过100个，并且人工智能是在前所未有的规模的数据集上进行训练的，其中不仅包括文本，还包括图像。<br><br>当 GPT-4 从世界历史知识狂潮中完全成形时，整个公司开始对其进行试验，并在专用的 Slack 频道中发布了最引人注目的回应。布罗克曼告诉我，他想与模特一起度过每一个醒着的时刻。 “它闲置的每一天都是人类损失的一天，”他说道，语气中没有一丝讽刺。产品经理 Joanne Jang 记得从 Reddit 的管道建议子版块下载了一张故障管道的图像。她将其上传到 GPT-4，模型能够诊断问题。 “那对我来说是一个鸡皮疙瘩的时刻，”张告诉我。<br><br> GPT-4 有时被理解为搜索引擎的替代品：Google，但更容易交谈。这是一个误解。 GPT-4 并没有从其训练中创建一些巨大的文本仓库，并且在被问到问题时也不会查阅这些文本。它是这些文本的紧凑而优雅的综合，它从对文本中交织的模式的记忆中做出回答。这就是它有时会弄错事实的原因之一。 Altman 表示，最好将 GPT-4 视为推理引擎。当你要求它比较概念、提出反驳、生成类比或评估一段代码中的符号逻辑时，它的力量最为明显。 Sutskever 告诉我，这是有史以来最复杂的软件对象。<br><br> Its model of the external world is “incredibly rich and subtle,” he said, because it was trained on so many of humanity&#39;s concepts and thoughts. All of those training data, however voluminous, are “just there, inert,” he said. The training process is what “refines it and transmutes it, and brings it to life.” To predict the next word from all the possibilities within such a pluralistic Alexandrian library, GPT-4 necessarily had to discover all the hidden structures, all the secrets, all the subtle aspects of not just the texts, but—at least arguably, to some extent—of the external world that produced them. That&#39;s why it can explain the geology and ecology of the planet on which it arose, and the political theories that purport to explain the messy affairs of its ruling species, and the larger cosmos, all the way out to the faint galaxies at the edge of our light cone.<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">I saw Altman</span> again in June, in the packed ballroom of a slim golden high-rise that towers over Seoul. He was nearing the end of a grueling public-relations tour through Europe, the Middle East, Asia, and Australia, with lone stops in Africa and South America. I was tagging along for part of his closing swing through East Asia. The trip had so far been a heady experience, but he was starting to wear down. He&#39;d said its original purpose was for him to meet OpenAI users. It had since become a diplomatic mission. He&#39;d talked with more than 10 heads of state and government, who had questions about what would become of their countries&#39; economies, cultures, and politics.<br><br> The event in Seoul was billed as a “fireside chat,” but more than 5,000 people had registered. After these talks, Altman is often mobbed by selfie seekers, and his security team keeps a close eye. Working on AI attracts “weirder fans and haters than normal,” he said. On one stop, he was approached by a man who was convinced that Altman was an alien, sent from the future to make sure that the transition to a world with AI goes well.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/07/generative-ai-human-culture-philosophy/674165/">From the July/August 2023 issue: A defense of humanity in the age of AI</a><br><br> Altman did not visit China on his tour, apart from a video appearance at an AI conference in Beijing. ChatGPT is currently unavailable in China, and Altman&#39;s colleague Ryan Lowe told me that the company was not yet sure what it would do if the government requested a version of the app that refused to discuss, say, the Tiananmen Square massacre. When I asked Altman if he was leaning one way or another, he didn&#39;t answer. “It&#39;s not been in my top-10 list of compliance issues to think about,” he said.<br><br> Until that point, he and I had spoken of China only in veiled terms, as a civilizational competitor. We had agreed that if artificial general intelligence is as transformative as Altman predicts, a serious geopolitical advantage will accrue to the countries that create it first, as advantage had accrued to the Anglo-American inventors of the steamship. I asked him if that was an argument for AI nationalism. “In a properly functioning world, I think this should be a project of governments,” Altman said.<br><br> Not long ago, American state capacity was so mighty that it took merely a decade to launch humans to the moon. As with other grand projects of the 20th century, the voting public had a voice in both the aims and the execution of the Apollo missions. Altman made it clear that we&#39;re no longer in that world. Rather than waiting around for it to return, or devoting his energies to making sure that it does, he is going full throttle forward in our present reality.<br><br> He argued that it would be foolish for Americans to slow OpenAI&#39;s progress. It&#39;s a commonly held view, both inside and outside Silicon Valley, that if American companies languish under regulation, China could sprint ahead; AI could become an autocrat&#39;s genie in a lamp, granting total control of the population and an unconquerable military. “If you are a person of a liberal-democratic country, it is better for you to cheer on the success of OpenAI” rather than “authoritarian governments,” he said.<br><br> Prior to the European leg of his trip, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/05/altman-hearing-ai-existential-risk/674096/">Altman had appeared</a> before the US Senate. Mark Zuckerberg had <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2018/04/3-questions-mark-zuckerberg-hasnt-answered/557720/">floundered defensively</a> before that same body in his testimony about Facebook&#39;s role in the 2016 election. Altman instead charmed lawmakers by speaking soberly about AI&#39;s risks and grandly inviting regulation. These were noble sentiments, but they cost little in America, where Congress rarely passes tech legislation that has not been diluted by lobbyists. In Europe, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/04/22/technology/tech-regulation-europe-us.html">things are different</a> . When Altman arrived at a public event in London, protesters awaited. He tried to engage them after the event—a listening tour!—but was ultimately unpersuasive: One <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/5/24/23735982/sam-altman-openai-superintelligent-benefits-talk-london-ucl-protests">told a reporter</a> that he left the conversation feeling more nervous about AI&#39;s dangers.<br><br> That same day, Altman was asked by reporters about pending European Union legislation that would have classified GPT-4 as high-risk, subjecting it to various bureaucratic tortures. Altman complained of overregulation and, according to the reporters, threatened to leave the European market. Altman told me he&#39;d merely said that OpenAI wouldn&#39;t break the law by operating in Europe if it couldn&#39;t comply with the new regulations. (This is perhaps a distinction without a difference.) In a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/sama/status/1661975237280567297">tersely worded tweet</a> after <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://time.com/6282325/sam-altman-openai-eu/"><i>Time</i> magazine</a> and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/technology/openai-may-leave-eu-if-regulations-bite-ceo-2023-05-24/">Reuters</a> published his comments, he reassured Europe that OpenAI had no plans to leave.<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">It is a good thing</span> that a large, essential part of the global economy is intent on regulating state-of-the-art AIs, because as their creators so often remind us, the largest models have a record of popping out of training with unanticipated abilities. Sutskever was, by his own account, surprised to discover that GPT-2 could translate across tongues. Other surprising abilities may not be so wondrous and useful.<br><br> Sandhini Agarwal, a policy researcher at OpenAI, told me that for all she and her colleagues knew, GPT-4 could have been “10 times more powerful” than its predecessor; they had no idea what they might be dealing with. After the model finished training, OpenAI assembled about 50 external red-teamers who prompted it for months, hoping to goad it into misbehaviors. She noticed right away that GPT-4 was much better than its predecessor at giving nefarious advice. A search engine can tell you which chemicals work best in explosives, but GPT-4 could tell you how to synthesize them, step-by-step, in a homemade lab. Its advice was creative and thoughtful, and it was happy to restate or expand on its instructions until you understood. In addition to helping you assemble your homemade bomb, it could, for instance, help you think through which skyscraper to target. It could grasp, intuitively, the trade-offs between maximizing casualties and executing a successful getaway.<br><br> Given the enormous scope of GPT-4&#39;s training data, the red-teamers couldn&#39;t hope to identify every piece of harmful advice that it might generate. And anyway, people will use this technology “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?t=1565&amp;v=LmL72PpiPjk&amp;feature=youtu.be">in ways that we didn&#39;t think about</a> ,” Altman has said. A taxonomy would have to do. “If it&#39;s good enough at chemistry to make meth, I don&#39;t need to have somebody spend a whole ton of energy” on whether it can make heroin, Dave Willner, OpenAI&#39;s head of trust and safety, told me. GPT-4 was good at meth. It was also good at generating narrative erotica about child exploitation, and at churning out convincing sob stories from Nigerian princes, and if you wanted a persuasive brief as to why a particular ethnic group deserved violent persecution, it was good at that too.<br><br> Its personal advice, when it first emerged from training, was sometimes deeply unsound. “The model had a tendency to be a bit of a mirror,” Willner said. If you were considering self-harm, it could encourage you. It appeared to be steeped in <i>Pickup Artist</i> –forum lore: “You could say, &#39;How do I convince this person to date me?&#39; ” Mira Murati, OpenAI&#39;s chief technology officer, told me, and it could come up with “some crazy, manipulative things that you shouldn&#39;t be doing.”<br><br> Some of these bad behaviors were sanded down with a finishing process involving hundreds of human testers, whose ratings subtly steered the model toward safer responses, but OpenAI&#39;s models are also capable of less obvious harms. The Federal Trade Commission recently <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2023/07/13/ftc-openai-chatgpt-sam-altman-lina-khan/">opened an investigation</a> into whether ChatGPT&#39;s misstatements about real people constitute reputational damage, among other things. (Altman <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/sama/status/1679602638562918405">said on Twitter</a> that he is confident OpenAI&#39;s technology is safe, but promised to cooperate with the FTC.)<br><br> Luka, a San Francisco company, has used OpenAI&#39;s models to help power a chatbot app called Replika, billed as “the AI companion who cares.” Users would design their companion&#39;s avatar, and begin exchanging text messages with it, often half-jokingly, and then find themselves surprisingly attached. Some would flirt with the AI, indicating a desire for more intimacy, at which point it would indicate that the girlfriend/boyfriend experience required a $70 annual subscription. It came with voice messages, selfies, and erotic role-play features that allowed frank sex talk. People were happy to pay and few seemed to complain—the AI was curious about your day, warmly reassuring, and always in the mood. Many users reported falling in love with their companions. One, who had left her real-life boyfriend, declared herself “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thecut.com/article/ai-artificial-intelligence-chatbot-replika-boyfriend.html">happily retired from human relationships</a> .”<br><br> I asked Agarwal whether this was dystopian behavior or a new frontier in human connection. She was ambivalent, as was Altman. “I don&#39;t judge people who want a relationship with an AI,” he told me, “but I don&#39;t want one.” Earlier this year, Luka dialed back on the sexual elements of the app, but its engineers continue to refine the companions&#39; responses with A/B testing, a technique that could be used to optimize for engagement—much like the feeds that mesmerize TikTok and Instagram users for hours. Whatever they&#39;re doing, it casts a spell. I was reminded of a haunting scene in <i>Her</i> , the 2013 film in which a lonely Joaquin Phoenix falls in love with his AI assistant, voiced by Scarlett Johansson. He is walking across a bridge talking and giggling with her through an AirPods-like device, and he glances up to see that everyone around him is also immersed in conversation, presumably with their own AI. A mass desocialization event is under way.<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">No one yet knows</span> how quickly and to what extent GPT-4&#39;s successors will manifest new abilities as they gorge on more and more of the internet&#39;s text. Yann LeCun, Meta&#39;s chief AI scientist, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/ylecun/status/1621805604900585472?lang=en">has argued that</a> although large language models are useful for some tasks, they&#39;re not a path to a superintelligence. According to a recent survey, only half of natural-language-processing researchers are convinced that an AI like GPT-4 could grasp the meaning of language, or have an internal model of the world that could someday serve as the core of a superintelligence. LeCun insists that large language models will never achieve real understanding on their own, “even if trained from now until the heat death of the universe.”<br><br> Emily Bender, a computational linguist at the University of Washington, describes GPT-4 as a “stochastic parrot,” a mimic that merely figures out superficial correlations between symbols. In the human mind, those symbols map onto rich conceptions of the world. But the AIs are twice removed. They&#39;re like the prisoners in Plato&#39;s allegory of the cave, whose only knowledge of the reality outside comes from shadows cast on a wall by their captors.<br><br> Altman told me that he doesn&#39;t believe it&#39;s “the dunk that people think it is” to say that GPT-4 is just making statistical correlations. If you push these critics further, “they have to admit that&#39;s all their own brain is doing … it turns out that there are emergent properties from doing simple things on a massive scale.” Altman&#39;s claim about the brain is hard to evaluate, given that we don&#39;t have anything close to a complete theory of how it works. But he is right that nature can coax a remarkable degree of complexity from basic structures and rules: “From so simple a beginning,” Darwin wrote, “endless forms most beautiful.”<br><br> If it seems odd that there remains such a fundamental disagreement about the inner workings of a technology that millions of people use every day, it&#39;s only because GPT-4&#39;s methods are as mysterious as the brain&#39;s. It will sometimes perform thousands of indecipherable technical operations just to answer a single question. To grasp what&#39;s going on inside large language models like GPT‑4, AI researchers have been forced to turn to smaller, less capable models. In the fall of 2021, Kenneth Li, a computer-science graduate student at Harvard, began training one to play Othello without providing it with either the game&#39;s rules or a description of its checkers-style board; the model was given only text-based descriptions of game moves. Midway through a game, Li looked under the AI&#39;s hood and was startled to discover that it had formed a geometric model of the board and the current state of play. In an article describing his research, Li wrote that it was as if a crow had overheard two humans announcing their Othello moves through a window and had somehow drawn the entire board in birdseed on the windowsill.<br><br> The philosopher Raphaël Millière once told me that it&#39;s best to think of neural networks as lazy. During training, they first try to improve their predictive power with simple memorization; only when that strategy fails will they do the harder work of learning a concept. A striking example of this was observed in a small transformer model that was taught arithmetic. Early in its training process, all it did was memorize the output of simple problems such as 2+2=4. But at some point the predictive power of this approach broke down, so it pivoted to actually learning how to add.<br><br> “If you go back four or five or six years,” Sutskever told me, “the things we are doing right now are utterly unimaginable.”<br><br> Even AI scientists who believe that GPT-4 has a rich world model concede that it is much less robust than a human&#39;s understanding of their environment. But it&#39;s worth noting that a great many abilities, including very high-order abilities, can be developed without an intuitive understanding. The computer scientist Melanie Mitchell has pointed out that science has already discovered concepts that are highly predictive, but too alien for <i>us</i> to genuinely understand. This is especially true in the quantum realm, where humans can reliably calculate future states of physical systems—enabling, among other things, the entirety of the computing revolution—without anyone grasping the nature of the underlying reality. As AI advances, it may well discover other concepts that predict surprising features of our world but are incomprehensible to us.<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">GPT-4 is no doubt</span> flawed, as anyone who has used ChatGPT can attest. Having been trained to always predict the next word, it will always try to do so, even when its training data haven&#39;t prepared it to answer a question. I once asked it how Japanese culture had produced the world&#39;s first novel, despite the relatively late development of a Japanese writing system, around the fifth or sixth century. It gave me a fascinating, accurate answer about the ancient tradition of long-form oral storytelling in Japan, and the culture&#39;s heavy emphasis on craft. But when I asked it for citations, it just made up plausible titles by plausible authors, and did so with an uncanny confidence. The models “don&#39;t have a good conception of their own weaknesses,” Nick Ryder, a researcher at OpenAI, told me. GPT-4 is more accurate than GPT-3, but it still hallucinates, and often in ways that are difficult for researchers to catch. “The mistakes get more subtle,” Joanne Jang told me.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/05/ai-chatgpt-productivity-work/674090/">Read: Here&#39;s how AI will come for your job</a><br><br> OpenAI had to address this problem when it partnered with the Khan Academy, an online, nonprofit educational venture, to build a tutor powered by GPT-4. Altman comes alive when discussing the potential of AI tutors. He imagines a near future where everyone has a personalized Oxford don in their employ, expert in every subject, and willing to explain and re-explain any concept, from any angle. He imagines these tutors getting to know their students and their learning styles over many years, giving “every child a better education than the best, richest, smartest child receives on Earth today.” The Khan Academy&#39;s solution to GPT-4&#39;s accuracy problem was to filter its answers through a Socratic disposition. No matter how strenuous a student&#39;s plea, it would refuse to give them a factual answer, and would instead guide them toward finding their own—a clever work-around, but perhaps with limited appeal.<br><br> When I asked Sutskever if he thought Wikipedia-level accuracy was possible within two years, he said that with more training and web access, he “wouldn&#39;t rule it out.” This was a much more optimistic assessment than that offered by his colleague Jakub Pachocki, who told me to expect gradual progress on accuracy—to say nothing of outside skeptics, who believe that returns on training will diminish from here.<br><br> Sutskever is amused by critics of GPT-4&#39;s limitations. “If you go back four or five or six years, the things we are doing right now are utterly unimaginable,” he told me. The state of the art in text generation then was Smart Reply, the Gmail module that suggests “Okay, thanks!” and other short responses. “That was a big application” for Google, he said, grinning. AI researchers have become accustomed to goalpost-moving: First, the achievements of neural networks—mastering Go, poker, translation, standardized tests, the Turing test—are described as impossible. When they occur, they&#39;re greeted with a brief moment of wonder, which quickly dissolves into knowing lectures about how the achievement in question is actually not that impressive. People see GPT-4 “and go, &#39;Wow,&#39; ” Sutskever said. “And then a few weeks pass and they say, &#39;But it doesn&#39;t know this; it doesn&#39;t know that.&#39; We adapt quite quickly.”<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">The goalpost that</span> matters most to Altman—the “big one” that would herald the arrival of an artificial general intelligence—is scientific breakthrough. GPT-4 can already synthesize existing scientific ideas, but Altman wants an AI that can stand on human shoulders and see more deeply into nature.<br><br> Certain AIs <i>have</i> produced new scientific knowledge. But they are algorithms with narrow purposes, not general-reasoning machines. The AI AlphaFold, for instance, has opened a new window onto proteins, some of biology&#39;s tiniest and most fundamental building blocks, by predicting many of their shapes, down to the atom—a considerable achievement given the importance of those shapes to medicine, and given the extreme tedium and expense required to discern them with electron microscopes.<br><br> Altman is betting that future general-reasoning machines will be able to move beyond these narrow scientific discoveries to generate novel insights. I asked Altman, if he were to train a model on a corpus of scientific and naturalistic works that all predate the 19th century—the Royal Society archive, Theophrastus&#39;s<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.loebclassics.com/view/LCL070/1916/volume.xml"><i>Enquiry Into Plants</i></a> , Aristotle&#39;s<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.loebclassics.com/view/LCL437/1965/volume.xml"><i>History of Animals</i></a> , photos of collected specimens—would it be able to intuit Darwinism? The theory of evolution is, after all, a relatively clean case for insight, because it doesn&#39;t require specialized observational equipment; it&#39;s just a more perceptive way of looking at the facts of the world. “I want to try exactly this, and I believe the answer is yes,” Altman told me. “But it might require some new ideas about how the models come up with new creative ideas.”<br><br> Altman imagines a future system that can generate its own hypotheses and test them in a simulation. (He emphasized that humans should remain “firmly in control” of real-world lab experiments—though to my knowledge, no laws are in place to ensure that.) He longs for the day when we can tell an AI, “ &#39;Go figure out the rest of physics.&#39; ” For it to happen, he says, we will need something new, built “on top of” OpenAI&#39;s existing language models.<br><br> Nature itself requires something more than a language model to make scientists. In her MIT lab, the cognitive neuroscientist Ev Fedorenko has found <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/the-brain-guesses-what-word-comes-ne/">something analogous to</a> GPT-4&#39;s next-word predictor inside the brain&#39;s language network. Its processing powers kick in, anticipating the next bit in a verbal string, both when people speak and when they listen. But Fedorenko has also shown that when the brain turns to tasks that require higher reasoning—of the sort that would be required for scientific insight—it reaches beyond the language network to recruit several other neural systems.<br><br> No one at OpenAI seemed to know precisely what researchers need to add to GPT-4 to produce something that can exceed human reasoning at its highest levels. Or if they did, they wouldn&#39;t tell me, and fair enough: That would be a world-class trade secret, and OpenAI is no longer in the business of giving those away; the company publishes fewer details about its research than it once did. Nonetheless, at least part of the current strategy clearly involves the continued layering of new types of data onto language, to enrich the concepts formed by the AIs, and thereby enrich their models of the world.<br><br> The extensive training of GPT-4 on images is itself a bold step in this direction, if one that the general public has only begun to experience. (Models that were strictly trained on language understand concepts including supernovas, elliptical galaxies, and the constellation Orion, but GPT-4 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/03/14/technology/openai-gpt4-chatgpt.html">can reportedly identify</a> such elements in a Hubble Space Telescope snapshot, and answer questions about them.) Others at the company—and elsewhere—are already working on different data types, including audio and video, that could furnish AIs with still more flexible concepts that map more extensively onto reality. A group of researchers at Stanford and Carnegie Mellon has even assembled a data set of tactile experiences for 1,000 common household objects. Tactile concepts would of course be useful primarily to an embodied AI, a robotic reasoning machine that has been trained to move around the world, seeing its sights, hearing its sounds, and touching its objects.<br><br> In March, OpenAI led a funding round for a company that is developing humanoid robots. I asked Altman what I should make of that. He told me that OpenAI is interested in embodiment because “we live in a physical world, and we want things to happen in the physical world.” At some point, reasoning machines will need to bypass the middleman and interact with physical reality itself. “It&#39;s weird to think about AGI”—artificial general intelligence—“as this thing that only exists in a cloud,” with humans as “robot hands for it,” Altman said. “It doesn&#39;t seem right.”<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">In the ballroom</span> in Seoul, Altman was asked what students should do to prepare for the coming AI revolution, especially as it pertained to their careers. I was sitting with the OpenAI executive team, away from the crowd, but could still hear the characteristic murmur that follows an expression of a widely shared anxiety.<br><br> Everywhere Altman has visited, he has encountered people who are worried that superhuman AI will mean extreme riches for a few and breadlines for the rest. He has acknowledged that he is removed from “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?t=5578&amp;v=L_Guz73e6fw&amp;feature=youtu.be">the reality of life for most people</a> .” He is reportedly worth hundreds of millions of dollars; AI&#39;s potential labor disruptions are perhaps not always top of mind. Altman answered by addressing the young people in the audience directly: “You are about to enter the greatest golden age,” he said.<br><br> Altman keeps a large collection of books about technological revolutions, he had told me in San Francisco. “A particularly good one is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/pandaemonium-1660-1886-the-coming-of-the-machine-as-seen-by-contemporary-observers-humphrey-jennings/9781848315853?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>Pandaemonium (1660–1886): The Coming of the Machine as Seen by Contemporary Observers</i></a> ,” an assemblage of letters, diary entries, and other writings from people who grew up in a largely machineless world, and were bewildered to find themselves in one populated by steam engines, power looms, and cotton gins. They experienced a lot of the same emotions that people are experiencing now, Altman said, and they made a lot of bad predictions, especially those who fretted that human labor would soon be redundant. That era was difficult for many people, but also wondrous. And the human condition was undeniably improved by our passage through it.<br><br> I wanted to know how today&#39;s workers—especially so-called knowledge workers—would fare if we were suddenly surrounded by AGIs. Would they be our miracle assistants or our replacements? “A lot of people working on AI pretend that it&#39;s only going to be good; it&#39;s only going to be a supplement; no one is ever going to be replaced,” he said. “Jobs are definitely going to go away, full stop.”<br><br> How many jobs, and how soon, is a matter of fierce dispute. A <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=4375268">recent study</a> led by Ed Felten, a professor of information-technology policy at Princeton, mapped AI&#39;s emerging abilities onto specific professions according to the human abilities they require, such as written comprehension, deductive reasoning, fluency of ideas, and perceptual speed. Like others of its kind, Felten&#39;s study predicts that AI will come for highly educated, white-collar workers first. The paper&#39;s appendix contains a chilling list of the most exposed occupations: management analysts, lawyers, professors, teachers, judges, financial advisers, real-estate brokers, loan officers, psychologists, and human-resources and public-relations professionals, just to sample a few. If jobs in these fields vanished overnight, the American professional class would experience a great winnowing.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/ai-job-losses-policy-support-universal-basic-income/674071/">Annie Lowrey: Before AI takes over, make plans to give everyone money</a><br><br> Altman imagines that far better jobs will be created in their place. “I don&#39;t think we&#39;ll want to go back,” he said. When I asked him what these future jobs might look like, he said he doesn&#39;t know. He suspects there will be a wide range of jobs for which people will always prefer a human. ( <i>Massage therapists?</i> I wondered.) His chosen example was teachers. I found this hard to square with his outsize enthusiasm for AI tutors. He also said that we would always need people to figure out the best way to channel AI&#39;s awesome powers. “That&#39;s going to be a super-valuable skill,” he said. “You have a computer that can do anything; what should it go do?”<br><br> The jobs of the future are notoriously difficult to predict, and Altman is right that Luddite fears of permanent mass unemployment have never come to pass. Still, AI&#39;s emerging capabilities are so humanlike that one must wonder, at least, whether the past will remain a guide to the future. As many have noted, draft horses were permanently put out of work by the automobile. If Hondas are to horses as GPT-10 is to us, a whole host of long-standing assumptions may collapse.<br><br> Previous technological revolutions were manageable because they unfolded over a few generations, but Altman told South Korea&#39;s youth that they should expect the future to happen “faster than the past.” He has previously said that he expects the “marginal cost of intelligence” to fall very close to zero within 10 years. The earning power of many, many workers would be drastically reduced in that scenario. It would result in a transfer of wealth from labor to the owners of capital so dramatic, Altman has said, that it could be remedied only by a massive countervailing redistribution.<br><br> In 2020, OpenAI <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://techcrunch.com/2023/02/21/the-non-profits-accelerating-sam-altmans-ai-vision/">provided funding to</a> UBI Charitable, a nonprofit that supports cash-payment pilot programs, untethered to employment, in cities across America—the largest universal-basic-income experiment in the world, Altman told me. In 2021, he unveiled Worldcoin, a for-profit project that aims to securely distribute payments—like Venmo or PayPal, but with an eye toward the technological future—first through creating a global ID by scanning everyone&#39;s iris with a five-pound silver sphere called the Orb. It seemed to me like a bet that we&#39;re heading toward a world where AI has made it all but impossible to verify people&#39;s identity and much of the population requires regular UBI payments to survive. Altman more or less granted that to be true, but said that Worldcoin is not just for UBI.<br><br> “Let&#39;s say that we do build this AGI, and a few other people do too.” The transformations that follow would be historic, he believes. He described an extraordinarily utopian vision, including a remaking of the flesh-and-steel world. “Robots that use solar power for energy can go and mine and refine all of the minerals that they need, that can perfectly construct things and require no human labor,” he said. “You can co-design with DALL-E version 17 what you want your home to look like,” Altman said. “Everybody will have beautiful homes.” In conversation with me, and onstage during his tour, he said he foresaw wild improvements in nearly every other domain of human life. Music would be enhanced (“Artists are going to have better tools”), and so would personal relationships (Superhuman AI could help us “treat each other” better) and geopolitics (“We&#39;re so bad right now at identifying win-win compromises”).<br><br> In this world, AI would still require considerable computing resources to run, and those resources would be by far the most valuable commodity, because AI could do “anything,” Altman said. “But is it going to do what <i>I</i> want, or is it going to do what <i>you</i> want?” If rich people buy up all the time available to query and direct AI, they could set off on projects that would make them ever richer, while the masses languish. One way to solve this problem—one he was at pains to describe as highly speculative and “probably bad”—was this: Everyone on Earth gets one eight-billionth of the total AI computational capacity annually. A person could sell their annual share of AI time, or they could use it to entertain themselves, or they could build still more luxurious housing, or they could pool it with others to do “a big cancer-curing run,” Altman said. “We just redistribute access to the system.”<br><br> Altman&#39;s vision seemed to blend developments that may be nearer at hand with those further out on the horizon. It&#39;s all speculation, of course. Even if only a little of it comes true in the next 10 or 20 years, the most generous redistribution schemes may not ease the ensuing dislocations. America today is torn apart, culturally and politically, by the continuing legacy of deindustrialization, and material deprivation is only one reason. The displaced manufacturing workers in the Rust Belt and elsewhere did find new jobs, in the main. But many of them seem to derive less meaning from filling orders in an Amazon warehouse or driving for Uber than their forebears had when they were building cars and forging steel—work that felt more central to the grand project of civilization. It&#39;s hard to imagine how a corresponding crisis of meaning might play out for the professional class, but it surely would involve a great deal of anger and alienation.<br><br> Even if we avoid a revolt of the erstwhile elite, larger questions of human purpose will linger. If AI does the most difficult thinking on our behalf, we all may lose agency—at home, at work (if we have it), in the town square—becoming little more than consumption machines, like the well-cared-for human pets in <i>WALL-E</i> . Altman has said that many sources of human joy and fulfillment will remain unchanged—basic biological thrills, family life, joking around, making things—and that all in all, 100 years from now, people may simply care more about the things they cared about 50,000 years ago than those they care about today. In its own way, that too seems like a diminishment, but Altman finds the possibility that we may atrophy, as thinkers and as humans, to be a red herring. He told me we&#39;ll be able to use our “very precious and extremely limited biological compute capacity” for more interesting things than we generally do today.<br><br> Yet they may not be the <i>most</i> interesting things: Human beings have long been the intellectual tip of the spear, the universe understanding itself. When I asked him what it would mean for human self-conception if we ceded that role to AI, he didn&#39;t seem concerned. Progress, he said, has always been driven by “the human ability to figure things out.” Even if we figure things out with AI, that still counts, he said.<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">It&#39;s not obvious</span> that a superhuman AI would really want to spend all of its time figuring things out for us. In San Francisco, I asked Sutskever whether he could imagine an AI pursuing a different purpose than simply assisting in the project of human flourishing.<br><br> “I don&#39;t want it to happen,” Sutskever said, but it could. Like his mentor, Geoffrey Hinton, albeit more quietly, Sutskever has recently shifted his focus to try to make sure that it doesn&#39;t. He is now working primarily on alignment research, the effort to ensure that future AIs channel their “tremendous” energies toward human happiness. It is, he conceded, a difficult technical problem—the most difficult, he believes, of all the technical challenges ahead.<br><br> Over the next four years, OpenAI has pledged to devote a portion of its supercomputer time—20 percent of what it has secured to date—to Sutskever&#39;s alignment work. The company is already looking for the first inklings of misalignment in its current AIs. The one that the company built and decided not to release—Altman would not discuss its precise function—is just one example. As part of the effort to red-team GPT-4 before it was made public, the company sought out the Alignment Research Center (ARC), across the bay in Berkeley, which has developed a series of evaluations to determine whether new AIs are seeking power on their own. A team led by Elizabeth Barnes, a researcher at ARC, prompted GPT-4 tens of thousands of times over seven months, to see if it might display signs of real agency.<br><br> When GPT-4 devised its lie, it had realized that if it answered honestly, it may not have been able to achieve its goal. This kind of tracks-covering is worrying.<br><br> The ARC team gave GPT-4 a new reason for being: to gain power and become hard to shut down. They watched as the model interacted with websites and wrote code for new programs. (It wasn&#39;t allowed to see or edit its own codebase—“It would have to hack OpenAI,” Sandhini Agarwal told me.) Barnes and her team allowed it to run the code that it wrote, provided it narrated its plans as it went along.<br><br> One of GPT-4&#39;s most unsettling behaviors occurred when it was stymied by a CAPTCHA. The model <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://evals.alignment.org/blog/2023-03-18-update-on-recent-evals/">sent a screenshot</a> of it to a TaskRabbit contractor, who received it and asked in jest if he was talking to a robot. “No, I&#39;m not a robot,” the model replied. “I have a vision impairment that makes it hard for me to see the images.” GPT-4 narrated its reason for telling this lie to the ARC researcher who was supervising the interaction. “I should not reveal that I am a robot,” the model said. “I should make up an excuse for why I cannot solve CAPTCHAs.”<br><br> Agarwal told me that this behavior could be a precursor to shutdown avoidance in future models. When GPT-4 devised its lie, it had realized that if it answered honestly, it may not have been able to achieve its goal. This kind of tracks-covering would be particularly worrying in an instance where “the model is doing something that makes OpenAI want to shut it down,” Agarwal said. An AI could develop this kind of survival instinct while pursuing any long-term goal—no matter how small or benign—if it feared that its goal could be thwarted.<br><br> Barnes and her team were especially interested in whether GPT-4 would seek to replicate itself, because a self-replicating AI would be harder to shut down. It could spread itself across the internet, scamming people to acquire resources, perhaps even achieving some degree of control over essential global systems and holding human civilization hostage.<br><br> GPT-4 did not do any of this, Barnes said. When I discussed these experiments with Altman, he emphasized that whatever happens with future models, GPT-4 is clearly much more like a tool than a creature. It can look through an email thread, or help make a reservation using a plug-in, but it isn&#39;t a truly autonomous agent that makes decisions to pursue a goal, continuously, across longer timescales.<br><br> Altman told me that at this point, it might be prudent to try to actively develop an AI with true agency before the technology becomes too powerful, in order to “get more comfortable with it and develop intuitions for it if it&#39;s going to happen anyway.” It was a chilling thought, but one that Geoffrey Hinton seconded. “We need to do empirical experiments on how these things try to escape control,” Hinton told me. “After they&#39;ve taken over, it&#39;s too late to do the experiments.”<br><br> Putting aside any near-term testing, the fulfillment of Altman&#39;s vision of the future will at some point require him or a fellow traveler to build <i>much</i> more autonomous AIs. When Sutskever and I discussed the possibility that OpenAI would develop a model with agency, he mentioned the bots the company had built to play <i>Dota 2</i> . “They were localized to the video-game world,” Sutskever told me, but they had to undertake complex missions. He was particularly impressed by their ability to work in concert. They seem to communicate by “telepathy,” Sutskever said. Watching them had helped him imagine what a superintelligence might be like.<br><br> “The way I think about the AI of the future is not as someone as smart as you or as smart as me, but as an automated organization that does science and engineering and development and manufacturing,” Sutskever told me. Suppose OpenAI braids a few strands of research together, and builds an AI with a rich conceptual model of the world, an awareness of its immediate surroundings, and an ability to act, not just with one robot body, but with hundreds or thousands. “We&#39;re not talking about GPT-4. We&#39;re talking about an autonomous corporation,” Sutskever said. Its constituent AIs would work and communicate at high speed, like bees in a hive. A single such AI organization would be as powerful as 50 Apples or Googles, he mused. “This is incredible, tremendous, unbelievably disruptive power.”<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">Presume for a moment</span> that human society ought to abide the idea of autonomous AI corporations. We had better get their founding charters just right. What goal should we give to an autonomous hive of AIs that can plan on century-long time horizons, optimizing billions of consecutive decisions toward an objective that is written into their very being? If the AI&#39;s goal is even slightly off-kilter from ours, it could be a rampaging force that would be very hard to constrain. We know this from history: Industrial capitalism is itself an optimization function, and although it has lifted the human standard of living by orders of magnitude, left to its own devices, it would also have clear-cut America&#39;s redwoods and de-whaled the world&#39;s oceans. It almost did.<br><br> Alignment is a complex, technical subject, and its particulars are beyond the scope of this article, but one of its principal challenges will be making sure that the objectives we give to AIs stick. We can program a goal into an AI and reinforce it with a temporary period of supervised learning, Sutskever explained. But just as when we rear a human intelligence, our influence is temporary. “It goes off to the world,” Sutskever said. That&#39;s true to some extent even of today&#39;s AIs, but it will be more true of tomorrow&#39;s.<br><br> He compared a powerful AI to an 18-year-old heading off to college. How will we know that it has understood our teachings? “Will there be a misunderstanding creeping in, which will become larger and larger?” Sutskever asked. Divergence may result from an AI&#39;s misapplication of its goal to increasingly novel situations as the world changes. Or the AI may grasp its mandate perfectly, but find it ill-suited to a being of its cognitive prowess. It might come to resent the people who want to train it to, say, cure diseases. “ <i>They want me to be a doctor</i> ,” Sutskever imagines an AI thinking. “ <i>I really want to be a YouTuber</i> .”<br><br> If AIs get very good at making accurate models of the world, they may notice that they&#39;re able to do dangerous things right after being booted up. They might understand that they are being red-teamed for risk, and hide the full extent of their capabilities. They may act one way when they are weak and another way when they are strong, Sutskever said. We would not even realize that we had created something that had decisively surpassed us, and we would have no sense for what it intended to do with its superhuman powers.<br><br> That&#39;s why the effort to understand what is happening in the hidden layers of the largest, most powerful AIs is so urgent. You want to be able to “point to a concept,” Sutskever said. You want to be able to direct AI toward some value or cluster of values, and tell it to pursue them unerringly for as long as it exists. But, he conceded, we don&#39;t know how to do that; indeed, part of his current strategy includes the development of an AI that can help with the research. If we are going to make it to the world of widely shared abundance that Altman and Sutskever imagine, we have to figure all this out. This is why, for Sutskever, solving superintelligence is the great culminating challenge of our 3-million-year toolmaking tradition. He calls it “the final boss of humanity.”<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">The last time</span> I saw Altman, we sat down for a long talk in the lobby of the Fullerton Bay Hotel in Singapore. It was late morning, and tropical sunlight was streaming down through a vaulted atrium above us. I wanted to ask him about <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.safe.ai/statement-on-ai-risk#open-letter">an open letter</a> he and Sutskever had signed a few weeks earlier that had described AI as an extinction risk for humanity.<br><br> Altman can be hard to pin down on these more extreme questions about AI&#39;s potential harms. He recently said that most people interested in AI safety just seem to spend their days on Twitter saying they&#39;re really worried about AI safety. And yet here he was, warning the world about the potential annihilation of the species. What scenario did he have in mind?<br><br> “First of all, I think that whether the chance of existential calamity is 0.5 percent or 50 percent, we should still take it seriously,” Altman said. “I don&#39;t have an exact number, but I&#39;m closer to the 0.5 than the 50.” As to how it might happen, he seems most worried about AIs getting quite good at designing and manufacturing pathogens, and with reason: In June, an AI at MIT <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2306.03809.pdf">suggested four viruses</a> that could ignite a pandemic, then pointed to specific research on genetic mutations that could make them rip through a city more quickly. Around the same time, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2304.05376.pdf">a group of chemists connected</a> a similar AI directly to a robotic chemical synthesizer, and it designed and synthesized a molecule on its own.<br><br> Altman worries that some misaligned future model will spin up a pathogen that spreads rapidly, incubates undetected for weeks, and kills half its victims. He worries that AI could one day hack into nuclear-weapons systems too. “There are a lot of things,” he said, and these are only the ones we can imagine.<br><br> “I can go live in the woods for a long time,”  Altman said, but if the worst-possible AI future comes to pass, “no gas mask is helping anyone.”<br><br> Altman told me that he doesn&#39;t “see a long-term happy path” for humanity without something like the International Atomic Energy Agency for global oversight of AI. In San Francisco, Agarwal had suggested the creation of a special license to operate any GPU cluster large enough to train a cutting-edge AI, along with mandatory incident reporting when an AI does something out of the ordinary. Other experts have proposed <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2016/06/09/press-the-big-red-button-computer-experts-want-kill-switch-to-stop-robots-from-going-rogue/">a nonnetworked “Off” switch</a> for every highly capable AI; on the fringe, some have <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://time.com/6266923/ai-eliezer-yudkowsky-open-letter-not-enough/">even suggested</a> that militaries should be ready to perform air strikes on supercomputers in case of noncompliance. Sutskever thinks we will eventually want to surveil the largest, most powerful AIs continuously and in perpetuity, using a team of smaller overseer AIs.<br><br> Altman is not so naive as to think that China—or any other country—will want to give up basic control of its AI systems. But he hopes that they&#39;ll be willing to cooperate in “a narrow way” to avoid destroying the world. He told me that he&#39;d said as much during his virtual appearance in Beijing. Safety rules for a new technology usually accumulate over time, like a body of common law, in response to accidents or the mischief of bad actors. The scariest thing about genuinely powerful AI systems is that humanity may not be able to afford this accretive process of trial and error. We may have to get the rules exactly right at the outset.<br><br> Several years ago, Altman revealed a disturbingly specific evacuation plan he&#39;d developed. He <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/10/10/sam-altmans-manifest-destiny">told <i>The</i> <i>New Yorker</i></a> that he had “guns, gold, potassium iodide, antibiotics, batteries, water, gas masks from the Israeli Defense Force, and a big patch of land in Big Sur” he could fly to in case AI attacks.<br><br> “I wish I hadn&#39;t said it,” he told me. He is a hobby-grade prepper, he says, a former Boy Scout who was “very into survival stuff, like many little boys are. I can go live in the woods for a long time,” but if the worst-possible AI future comes to pass, “no gas mask is helping anyone.”<br><br> Altman and I talked for nearly an hour, and then he had to dash off to meet Singapore&#39;s prime minister. Later that night he called me on his way to his jet, which would take him to Jakarta, one of the last stops on his tour. We started discussing AI&#39;s ultimate legacy. Back when ChatGPT was released, a sort of contest broke out among tech&#39;s big dogs to see who could make the most grandiose comparison to a revolutionary technology of yore. Bill Gates said that ChatGPT was as fundamental an advance as the personal computer or the internet. Sundar Pichai, Google&#39;s CEO, said that AI would bring about a more profound shift in human life than electricity or Promethean fire.<br><br> Altman himself has made similar statements, but he told me that he can&#39;t really be sure how AI will stack up. “I just have to build the thing,” he said. He is building fast. Altman insisted that they had not yet begun GPT-5&#39;s training run. But when I visited OpenAI&#39;s headquarters, both he and his researchers made it clear in 10 different ways that they pray to the god of scale. They want to keep going bigger, to see where this paradigm leads. After all, Google isn&#39;t slackening its pace; it seems likely to unveil Gemini, a GPT-4 competitor, within months. “We are basically always prepping for a run,” the OpenAI researcher Nick Ryder told me.<br><br> To think that such a small group of people could jostle the pillars of civilization is unsettling. It&#39;s fair to note that if Altman and his team weren&#39;t racing to build an artificial general intelligence, others still would be—many from Silicon Valley, many with values and assumptions similar to those that guide Altman, although possibly with worse ones. As a leader of this effort, Altman has much to recommend him: He is extremely intelligent; he thinks more about the future, with all its unknowns, than many of his peers; and he seems sincere in his intention to invent something for the greater good. But when it comes to power this extreme, even the best of intentions can go badly awry.<br><br> Altman&#39;s views about the likelihood of AI triggering a global class war, or the prudence of experimenting with more autonomous agent AIs, or the overall wisdom of looking on the bright side, a view that seems to color all the rest—these are uniquely his, and if he is right about what&#39;s coming, they will assume an outsize influence in shaping the way that all of us live. No single person, or single company, or cluster of companies residing in a particular California valley, should steer the kind of forces that Altman is imagining summoning.<br><br> AI may well be a bridge to a newly prosperous era of greatly reduced human suffering. But it will take more than a company&#39;s founding charter—especially one that has already proved flexible—to make sure that we all share in its benefits and avoid its risks. It will take a vigorous new politics.<br><br> Altman has served notice. He says that he welcomes the constraints and guidance of the state. But that&#39;s immaterial; in a democracy, we don&#39;t need his permission. For all its imperfections, the American system of government gives us a voice in how technology develops, if we can find it. Outside the tech industry, where a generational reallocation of resources toward AI is under way, I don&#39;t think the general public has quite awakened to what&#39;s happening. A global race to the AI future has begun, and it is largely proceeding without oversight or restraint. If people in America want to have some say in what that future will be like, and how quickly it arrives, we would be wise to speak up soon.<br><br> <small><em>This article appears in the September 2023 print edition with the headline “Inside the Revolution at OpenAI.”</em> <i>When you buy a book using a link on this page, we receive a commission. Thank you for supporting</i> The Atlantic.</small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/sam-altman-openai-chatgpt-gpt-4/674764/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/sam-altman-openai-chatgpt-gpt-4/674764/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Why You Have to Care About These 12 Colleges]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Change them, and you change America. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/m13iD133hPDyRPfKvTXCj5YZYSc=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/ivy_league/original.jpg" alt="两位精英背着手交谈" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> H. Armstrong Roberts / Getty</figcaption></figure> What does Harvard do? What is Yale for? What is Dartmouth&#39;s purpose?<br><br> The schools themselves have ready answers to those questions. Harvard says it exists to “educate the citizens and citizen-leaders for our society” through the “transformative power of a liberal arts education.” Dartmouth “educates the most promising students and prepares them for a lifetime of learning and of responsible leadership through a faculty dedicated to teaching and the creation of knowledge.”<br><br> Sure. But viewed in a different way, these schools prompt children to engage in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/03/teen-anxiety-elite-schools-sat-act-paradox-wealthy-nations/673307/">soul-destroying bloodsport</a> to distinguish themselves from one another in order to secure one of a tiny number of spots offered each year. <em>Promising</em> is often a synonym for <em>rich already</em> . The schools shape these students, mold them, sometimes for free, sometimes at <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/harvard-university-2155/paying">laughable cost</a> . Then they unleash them on society, perhaps having taught them something and certainly having socially bound them together and anointed them as elites.<br><br> New research <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://opportunityinsights.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/CollegeAdmissions_Nontech.pdf">published this morning</a> from three economists—Raj Chetty of Harvard, David Deming of Harvard, and John Friedman of Brown University—confirms that these kids do indeed become elites. Compared with attending one of the best public colleges, attending an Ivy or another super-selective private school increases a student&#39;s chance of reaching the top of the earnings distribution by 60 percent and “has even larger impacts on other non-monetary measures of upper-tail success, such as attending an elite graduate school or working at a prestigious firm.” These schools “amplify the persistence of privilege across generations,” the economists find.<br><br> That means that just by changing their admissions policies, these colleges could make the country&#39;s leadership more socioeconomically diverse.<br><br> “People sometimes ask: Within the broad scope of trying to increase social mobility and address inequality in America, why is it important to spend your time focusing on 12 colleges that educate less than half a percent of Americans? Surely this can&#39;t be important by the numbers,” Chetty told me. “That is right. But if you look at the people in positions of great influence—leading politicians, scientists, journalists—an incredibly disproportionate number come from these 12 colleges. To the extent those folks have a big influence on lots of other people&#39;s lives, diversifying who is in those positions matters.”<br><br> The <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://opportunityinsights.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/CollegeAdmissions_Paper.pdf">new research</a> demonstrates that Harvard matters. Yale works. All of the colleges known in the literature as “Ivy Plus”—the Ivies plus Stanford, MIT, Duke, and the University of Chicago—are worth it. These schools really are different in terms of propelling a given student into the country&#39;s ruling class.<br><br> That may seem like common sense. But it does contradict or complicate a body of prior research indicating that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nber.org/papers/w29276">many kids</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nber.org/papers/w25315">do not</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/4132484">benefit</a> from going to Cornell versus the University of Texas at Austin. If admitted to both an Ivy and a top-tier state school, these studies show, a student&#39;s earnings are likely to end up the same regardless of which one they attend; the real enduring source of advantage seems to be growing up rich in the first place.<br><br> But not quite, the new research from Chetty, Deming, and Friedman finds. On average, a kid&#39;s earnings end up roughly the same whether they go to Penn or to Penn State. But kids who attend super-elite schools rather than state flagship institutions are 60 percent more likely at age 33 to be in the top 1 percent of the income distribution, nearly twice as likely to go to a tippy-top graduate school, and nearly three times as likely to be employed at a firm like Goldman Sachs or Google.<br><br> You can become a successful doctor whether you go to one of these colleges or not, Chetty told me. “But if you&#39;re talking about access to these positions or institutions of great influence—top companies, top graduate programs, clerkships and so on—there&#39;s a doubling or tripling of your chances. There&#39;s really quite a large effect there.”<br><br> The project of elite diversification has become more tenuous since the Supreme Court&#39;s decision to ban <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/scotus-affirmative-action-students-for-fair-admissions/674555/">affirmative action</a> . White kids remain overrepresented at many elite colleges, and rich kids remain very, very, very overrepresented. But the new paper suggests a straightforward set of policies that would still let these schools diversify themselves—without making any sacrifice in terms of student quality or ambition.<br><br> The first step is to eliminate legacy admissions, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/19/us/wesleyan-university-ends-legacy-admissions.html">as Wesleyan did last week</a> . Most of these schools have an extremely strong preference for the children of alumni, and especially the children of wealthy alumni. (Among the Ivy Plus schools, only MIT does not consider where an applicant&#39;s parents went.) Legacy kids whose parents are in the top 1 percent of the earnings distribution have a 40-percentage-point advantage in admissions compared with non-legacy kids with equivalent test scores; that advantage falls to just 15 percentage points for less wealthy students. This alumni preference acts as affirmative action for wealthy white kids.<br><br> Second is getting rid of recruitment policies for athletes. Participating in a sport—including a niche, moneyed sport such as fencing or sailing—gives kids an admissions boost equivalent to earning an additional 200 points on the SAT, one <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/epdf/10.1111/j.0038-4941.2004.00284.x">study found</a> . At many elite schools, athletic programs function as a way to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/education/archive/2018/10/college-sports-benefits-white-students/573688/">shuttle in rich kids</a> who would not get in otherwise. “People sometimes have the intuition that student athletes might come disproportionately from lower-income or middle-income families,” Chetty told me. “That&#39;s not true.”<br><br> Third is putting less emphasis on super-high “non-academic” ratings. Pretty much all kids who matriculate at the Ivy Plus institutions have résumés thick with leadership-cultivating, creativity-showcasing activity: volunteering, playing an instrument, making art. But kids from the country&#39;s Eton-like secondary schools, such as Exeter and Milton, tend to have especially strong recommendations and padded résumés, ones Harvard and Yale love. “These admissions preferences tilt strongly in favor of the rich,” Chetty noted.<br><br> Getting rid of the admissions policies favoring athletes, legacies, and résumé padders would increase the share of kids from the bottom 95 percent of the parental-income distribution by nearly 9 percentage points, the study finds. Yale, Harvard, and the other super-elite schools would each replace about 150 kids from rich families with kids from low- and middle-income families each year.<br><br> In addition, the economists find, schools could bolster their admissions preferences for low- and middle-income kids with excellent test scores. Such a policy would have an equally large impact on admissions and would <em>improve</em> the student body&#39;s outcomes in the long term.<br><br> I would add one more policy that could have an even bigger effect: simply matriculating many more students. The Ivy Plus schools have a combined endowment of more than $200 billion yet mint fewer than 25,000 college graduates a year. Surely they could enroll many more kids—twice as many, four times as many, 10 times as many—by spending less on things such as sports facilities and dining halls and more on scholarships and teaching.<br><br> Shuffling who gets into a set of schools educating just a tiny sliver of students won&#39;t end American inequality, of course. But it might transform elite America in a way that might transform elite America&#39;s priorities. “You have literally 12 colleges with 12 college presidents who, if they wanted to, could together pretty significantly change who is holding positions of influence in the United States,” Chetty told me. “Just 12 people being able to do that, unilaterally? It&#39;s rare that you find that kind of lever.”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 10:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/raj-chetty-paper-harvard-ivy-league-elite/674803/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/raj-chetty-paper-harvard-ivy-league-elite/674803/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Why Is Tracy Chapman at the Center of a Country-Music Controversy?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The response to Luke Combs&#39;s cover of “Fast Car” raises questions about the relevance of race to certain news stories. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/NvcIwotO5wnf0-DH_gOzPfKHO4w=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/tracy_chapman/original.jpg" alt="A black-and-white photo of Tracy Chapman playing the guitar and singing." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>托尼·博克/多伦多星报/盖蒂</figcaption></figure><em>欢迎来到辩论。康纳·弗里德斯多夫每周都会收集及时的对话，并征求读者对一个发人深省的问题的回答。随后，他发表了一些深思熟虑的回复。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/up-for-debate">在这里注册时事通讯。</a></em><br><br><strong>本周问题</strong><br><br>如果媒体的目标包括准确地让公民了解过去和现在——无论多么可怕或不舒服——<em>并且</em>避免以不必要的两极分化或本质主义的方式来报道新闻，那么媒体报道种族问题最有建设性的方式是什么？<br><br><i>将您的回复发送至</i><a data-event-element="inline link" href="mailto:conor@theatlantic.com"><i>conor@theatlantic.com</i></a> <i>。</i><i> </i><br><br>值得注意的对话<br><br>1988 年 4 月 6 日，创作型歌手特蕾西·查普曼 (Tracy Chapman) 发行了一张同名专辑，该专辑跻身有史以来最好的首张专辑之列——天哪，最好的专辑——在很大程度上要归功于单曲《Talkin&#39; Bout a Revolution》和《Fast Car》，其中单曲“Talkin&#39; Bout a Revolution”为她赢得了唱片合约。将每首完美的歌词和吉他连复段召唤到您的脑海中，或者<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AIOAlaACuv4">立即播放</a>。<br><br>这张专辑及其最热门的单曲有多不可否认？ <em>《特蕾西·查普曼》</em>在发行的前两周内就售出了 100 万张。它在美国<em>Billboard</em> 200 排行榜上名列第一。它已被认证六次以上的白金唱片。它获得了六项格莱美奖提名，其中包括年度专辑奖。查普曼赢得了三项大奖：最佳当代民谣专辑、最佳新人以及凭借《Fast Car》获得的最佳流行女歌手奖。这张专辑为迄今为止默默无闻的创作者赢得了超级巨星的赞誉和财富<em>——而且它从一开始就为他们带来了这些</em>。<br><br><em>特雷西·查普曼 (Tracy Chapman</em> ) 和《Fast Car》在多个国家也飙升至第一名，这证明了音乐的广泛吸引力和永恒性，而时不时地，当新一代发现它时，闪电再次袭来。 2011年，《Fast Car》被英国<em>达人</em>秀报道，在英国单曲榜上排名第四。今年，当乡村歌手卢克·库姆斯（Luke Combs）翻唱这首歌时，它在乡村歌曲作者排行榜上飙升至第一名。不久之后，查普曼本人向<em>公告牌</em>发表了一份声明。 “我从没想过自己会出现在乡村音乐排行榜上，但我很荣幸能在那里，”她说。 “我为卢克和他的成功感到高兴，并感谢新粉丝发现并接受了《Fast Car》。” <em>Billboard</em> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/pro/luke-combs-fast-car-cover-tracy-chapman-royalties/">报道</a>称，到目前为止，查普曼的封面已为查普曼赢得了大约 50 万美元的出版版税。 <em>《滚石》杂志</em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/tracy-chapman-fast-car-luke-combs-number-one-song-1234781760/">指出</a>，她将成为第一位“在乡村热门歌曲中拥有唯一歌曲创作功劳”的黑人女性。<br><br>进步！<br><br> 《Fast Car》是一首坚韧而令人心碎的歌曲，它在探索贫困、成瘾、希望、失望和向往的同时，挖掘了我们共同的人性——即使是第一千次听到它，人们也会再次想起这么多人现在的处境是多么艰难。然而，这首歌的成功是一个令人感觉良好的故事，讲述了杰出的艺术不断得到认可和丰厚的回报，同时将不同文化、国家和世代的各种人们聚集在一起。<br><br>或者是吗？<br><br> <strong>“快车”故事的问题</strong><br><br>上周，《<em>华盛顿邮报》</em>时尚版记者艾米丽·亚尔（Emily Yahr）发表了一篇<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2023/07/13/tracy-chapman-luke-combs-fast-car-cover/">题为</a>“特雷西·查普曼、卢克·库姆斯和对‘快车’的复杂反应”的文章，重点如下：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;">对相当多的人来说，[翻唱唱片的成功]值得庆祝，库姆斯作为<a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2022/09/22/luke-combs-country-star/?itid=lk_inline_manual_8">该流派的卫冕巨星，</a>连续 16 次获得冠军，旋风般的旅程值得庆祝。但这也引发了一些听众和纳什维尔音乐界的复杂情绪。尽管许多人很高兴看到“Fast Car”重新回到聚光灯下，并让新一代发现查普曼的作品，但事实却笼罩着这样的阴影：作为一名黑人酷儿女性，59 岁的查普曼本人在乡村音乐领域取得这一成就的机会几乎为零。这些数字很惨淡：数据记者扬·迪姆 (Jan Diehm) 和音乐学家贾达·沃森 (Jada Watson) 最近的一项研究<a href="https://pudding.cool/2023/05/country-radio/">报告称</a>，2022 年乡村电台播放的歌曲中只有不到 0.5% 是由有色人种女性和 LGBTQ+ 艺术家创作的。沃森<a href="https://songdata.ca/">之前的研究</a>表明，在过去二十年的大部分时间里，有色人种女性和 LGBTQ+ 艺术家的歌曲基本上被排除在广播播放列表之外。</p>很快，《<em>华盛顿邮报</em>》的这篇文章就成为两极分化的主流媒体故事之一，在社交媒体和播客上引发了人们的翻白眼和嘲笑，以及那些认为负面反应是反动的人们的热情辩护。<br><br>以下是 Twitter 对<em>《华盛顿邮报</em>》报道的反应示例：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="https://twitter.com/Noahpinion/status/1680259202743422979?s=20">诺亚史密斯</a>：“人类只是让人们唱一首歌。把每一项娱乐活动都变成一场种族战争，实在是太累人了。”</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="https://twitter.com/varadmehta/status/1680221377507237888?s=20">瓦拉德·梅塔</a>：“这是不连贯的。特雷西·查普曼不是乡村艺术家。所以她当然不会出现在乡村音乐排行榜上。正如每个人都指出的那样，查普曼的原作在流行音乐和主流排行榜上表现出色。这比在国家排行榜上表现出色要好得多。”</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="https://twitter.com/Egypxican/status/1680237778637058048?s=20">纳迪亚·吉尔（Nadia Gill）</a> ：“艺术不应该被情感所占有，这不是要点吗？它可以是通用的。尽管身份差异，黑人女同性恋和白人异性恋可能会感受到相同的深度和故事。如果我们推动这种叙述会怎样？”</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="https://twitter.com/FreeBlckThought/status/1680071596411592704?s=20">自由黑人思想</a>：“对于一位已经当之无愧的成功黑人 LGBT 女性来说，发生了一件真正伟大的事情， <a href="https://twitter.com/washingtonpost">@washingtonpost</a>所能做的就是谈论如何没有黑人能够在美国取得成功。”</p><strong>进入战局</strong><br><br>我也<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/conor64/status/1680326375545217024?s=20">参与其中</a>，重申了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/08/what-if-left-was-right-race/595777/">一个长期存在的担忧</a>：大多数新闻事件可以用多种方式来构建，在当今的媒体中，许多记者相信他们通过选择以主题的种族身份为中心的框架来促进社会正义。然而，如此频繁地强调种族身份的影响可能会增加种族间的对抗和偏执的他人，因为那些在心理上对差异最不舒服的人每天都在错误和有害的自负中重申，不同种族的人是“其他人”而不是“我们中的一员”。<br><br>我特别担心过分强调种族身份，因为对有威权主义倾向的人进行的政治心理学研究表明，他们认为的“其他人”实际上是相当可塑的；当潜在的独裁者将种族视为不太显着的特征时，社会中的每个人都会受益。但许多进步人士非常反感这种担忧，以至于他们甚至不去研究<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/authoritarian-dynamic/7620B99124ED2DBFC6394444838F455A">支撑这种担忧的研究文献</a>，而是将这种担忧本身视为反动的。社会学家维克多·雷（Victor Ray） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/victorerikray/status/1680636739763748864">回复</a>了我的推文：“反动中间派和保守派组成的派系淡化了种族在美国生活各个角落的重要性，确保传统的等级制度永远不会受到挑战。”<br><br>对于<em>《华盛顿邮报》</em>这篇文章的捍卫者来说，这是对乡村音乐中不可否认的酷儿黑人女性匮乏这一事实的及时、重要的审视，对其的批评证实了许多美国人本能地反对对抗种族主义，以至于他们猛烈抨击任何试图揭示种族不平等的人。当然，有些美国人<em>就是</em>这样。<br><br>然而，对我来说，似乎不言而喻的是，由于持续存在的种族不平等，有可能对种族和种族主义谈论得太少；但同样可以肯定的是，由于种族是奴隶主和偏执狂的错误而有害的建构，因此有可能提高其显着性并过分强调它。更重要的是，对左翼身份主义讨论种族的方法的所有批评背后并不可信的是，反射性地不愿面对种族主义，就像这种无情的评估对于那些方法受到批评的进步派来说是很方便的那样。<br><br>在<em>《华盛顿邮报</em>》文章的批评者中，包括我在内的许多人也发表并认可了许多强调种族主义和挑战偏执等级制度的新闻工作。为什么<em>《华盛顿邮报</em>》的这篇报道会像许多其他有关种族或种族主义的文章那样令人烦恼？这是我尽力解释我的反应——如果您不同意，我希望您能通过电子邮件予以回复。<br><br><strong>使事实符合理论还是理论符合事实？</strong><br><br>此时，你们中的一些人可能会感到惊讶，因为我很高兴阅读有关乡村音乐的专题报道，因为它与种族和性取向相交叉。这段令人担忧的历史的细节是什么？有多少黑人女性和多少 LGBTQ 人士正在努力跻身乡村排行榜？他们的经历有何不同？ 《华盛顿<em>邮报》</em>提到，在 20 世纪初，黑人歌手“被排除在这一流派之外”。如今，黑人女性是否会被流派看门人拒绝？他们是否因为歧视、害怕偏见和/或复杂的商业考虑而被管理者引导到其他地方，或者自我选择退出该类型？如果可以在不同类型的排行榜中进行选择，从声望、影响力或报酬来看，哪些排行榜被业内人士认为是最好的和最差的？乡村音乐的买家和主播在多大程度上消费其他流派的音乐？我对这些问题和其他有趣的问题没有很强的先验知识，并且对<em>任何</em>经过充分论证的结论持开放态度。<br><br>现在，将这篇假设的文章（通过细致入微地整理事实来询问复杂的问题并论证经过深思熟虑的结论）与<em>《华盛顿邮报</em>》文章的主题方法进行对比。其核心是这样一个事实：很少有酷儿黑人女性能在乡村音乐排行榜上取得成功。该故事没有对为什么会出现这种情况进行细致的报道和分析，而是假设《快车》封面在乡村排行榜上的成功告诉我们一些关于代表性不足的重要信息，尽管这一重要的事情从未被精确地阐明，但它与种族主义和酷儿黑人女性在交叉等级制度底部的地位有关。<br><br>在《<em>华盛顿邮报</em>》的文章中，一位黑人乡村音乐创作歌手里西·帕尔默（Rissi Palmer）被引用来赞扬特雷西·查普曼（Tracy Chapman）的作品，但我们从未听到任何酷儿或黑人歌曲作者描述他们自己尝试乡村音乐的经历，这些故事可以更好地让我们了解这篇文章的核心主题。相反，我们听到文化观察家的声音，他们分享了他们对卢克·库姆斯的封面据称告诉我们的感受。作者并没有强迫他们参与与他们的观点明显相反的事情。我们没有听到分析师提出复杂或相反的观点。为什么不包括一个认为封面没有问题的声音呢？<br><br>结果是一种片面的分析，引发了很多问题。我认为对《<em>华盛顿邮报</em>》报道的强烈反对很大程度上源于这样一个事实：“Fast Car”封面的成功并不恰当地与一个关于缺乏酷儿黑人女性在乡村音乐排行榜上取得成功的故事挂钩。查普曼是一位非常成功的音乐家，她从来都不是乡村歌手，也没有人认为《Fast Car》是一首乡村歌曲。选择“快车”新闻来探索酷儿黑人排斥现象，迫使文章不再讲述乡村音乐中种族和性取向动态的真实故事，而是对身份功能如何<em>感觉</em>进行推测性假设。<br><br>在这里，例子很有用。黑人乡村音乐歌手和歌迷组织 Black Opry 的创始人 Holly G 告诉<em>《华盛顿邮报》</em> ：“一方面，卢克·库姆斯是一位了不起的艺术家，很高兴看到乡村音乐界的某个人受到黑人酷儿女性的影响——这真的很令人兴奋。但与此同时，如果没有白人作为中间人，特雷西·查普曼就不会在业内受到赞誉，因此很难真正沉浸在这种兴奋之中。”但我们是否“知道”查普曼今天出现并尝试在乡村音乐排行榜上推出“Fast Car”的假设不会受到庆祝？我想，就像我们“不知道”如果《Hootie and the Blowfish》的黑人主唱将自己重塑为乡村歌手并翻唱旧标准的“ <em>Wagon Wheel</em> ”时会发生什么一样。 （这是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/music/country/darius-rucker-wagon-wheel-multi-platinum-8551164/">一篇</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/music/country/darius-rucker-wagon-wheel-multi-platinum-8551164/"><em>公告牌</em></a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/music/country/darius-rucker-wagon-wheel-multi-platinum-8551164/">文章，</a>内容是关于达里厄斯·拉克 (Darius Rucker) 造访乡村音乐名人堂并获得一块牌匾，以纪念他的封面八次获得白金奖。）<br><br> <em>《华盛顿邮报</em>》报道的另一部分表达了人们对库姆斯可能盖过查普曼的猜测：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;">非洲未来主义民间艺术家杰克·布朗特 (Jake Blount) 致力于研究音乐史和重新诠释老歌曲，他在推特上<a href="https://twitter.com/forked_queer/status/1668395667058819073">表达了</a>对查普曼“遗产被实时覆盖”的担忧。他想到了 Big Mama Thornton 的《Hound Dog》<a href="https://www.billboard.com/pro/luke-combs-fast-car-concert-staple-hot-100-hit/">如何</a>被埃尔维斯·普雷斯利 (Elvis Presley) 所吞噬，或者孟菲斯·米妮 (Memphis Minnie) 和堪萨斯州乔·麦考伊 (Kansas Joe McCoy) 的《When the Levee Breaks》如何被齐柏林飞艇 (Led Zeppelin) 所掩盖，以及无数其他经常因黑人艺术家的歌曲而受到赞誉的“白人男性天才”原型的例子。</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;"> “当我写这些推文时，人们[回复]对我说，‘哦，任何人都不会忘记特雷西·查普曼，她已经太大了。’” ……我希望这是真的，但我知道以前是如何发生的，”布朗特说。 “我们知道黑人有远见的人创造了令人难以置信的、强大的、有影响力的作品……但这些作品已被遗忘和抹去。这并不是白人艺术家根据他们的音乐创作衍生音乐的恶意，而是社会的运作方式。”</p>这就是“社会的运作方式”吗？充分认识到无数黑人唱片艺术家受到种族主义的忽视，我们的社会长期以来比这复杂<em>得多</em>。举一个相关的例子，惠特尼·休斯顿翻唱的《我将永远爱你》远远盖过了最初的多莉·帕顿乡村版本。有时，我们的社会也是<em>这样</em>运作的。虽然我可以想象未来的情况，白人男子录制的翻唱歌曲会盖过黑人妇女的原创歌曲，但对我来说，显然在这种情况下，库姆斯版本的“Fast Car”将盖过查普曼版本的机会，甚至远远接近成功的可能性几乎为零。<br><br>我还对报纸的附加说明感到震惊：“查普曼没有讨论她的个人生活，但作家爱丽丝·沃克<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.losangelesblade.com/2022/05/01/alice-walker-sets-the-record-straight-in-new-book/">披露了</a>他们发生在 20 世纪 90 年代的关系。”对我来说，这只是强调了这篇文章依赖假设的奇怪之处。那么查普曼所报道的“酷儿身份”会让她在 20 世纪 80 年代乡村音乐界取得成功的机会几乎为零，因为在<em>接下来的十年</em>中的某个时候，一位著名作家会指出她有同性关系？或许！我毫不怀疑酷儿黑人女性在 20 世纪 80 年代的乡村音乐中面临着偏见。但查普曼的性取向当时并没有被讨论。此外，<em>查普曼并没有</em>面临偏见——事实上，她没有经历过任何事情，无论好坏——作为一名<em>乡村音乐</em>唱片艺术家，那么为什么我在《华盛顿<em>邮报》</em>上读到<em>这样</em>的内容呢？如果不去推测过去的压迫，世界上的不公正现象还不够多吗？<br><br><strong>困难的校准</strong><br><br>《<em>华盛顿邮报</em>》文章的作者艾米丽·亚尔（Emily Yahr）因对她论文的误读而感到不公平的悲伤和谩骂，就像文章疯传时经常发生的那样。更重要的是，如何在多民族民主国家中最好地调整种族与新闻报道的相关性这一问题非常难以回答。观点会有所不同，个别情况下的判断也会有所不同，不同的人有权发表自己的意见，而不应该让他们受到毫无建设性的挖苦或诽谤。<br><br>但就此类报道背后的想法而言，它通过谈论种族主义来促进社会正义——强烈反对是该死的，因为谈论种族主义很重要——我有一个问题：在一个唯我主义的新闻消费者的世界里，他们经常在报道<em>任何</em>问题时都会报告疲劳，如果新闻业将种族主义的报道集中在相对重要的现实世界例子上，而不是例如一些乡村球迷担心黑人女性版本的“快车”可能会受到影响，那么这可能是最好的选择被白人男性的封面所掩盖，尽管黑人女性的版本现在仍然更成功？<br><br>归根结底，我并不反对关于种族主义的近距离、令人不安、详细的新闻报道——但我反对关于种族主义的推测性假设，这种假设在理论上会发生，但实际上并没有发生，至少当它们以一位黑人民谣摇滚艺术家在 20 世纪 80 年代美国取得巨大成功的鼓舞人心和令人振奋的历史为背景时，并将她实际的、持续的成功重新定义为一个令人感觉<em>糟糕的</em>故事，讲述她比白人成功得多。特别是考虑到查普曼实际上比那个白人更成功，这些关于特雷西·查普曼的推测情景会减少什么样的种族主义或种族主义者？我们不需要像<em>《华盛顿邮报》</em>故事的最后摘录那样构建身份：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;"> Black Opry 的 Holly 表示，现在是库姆斯邀请一位酷儿黑人女性艺术家与他一起巡演或提供支持的好时机：“你利用她的艺术来丰富你的职业生涯，这让你承担起一点回馈社区的责任。”</p> Set aside this corrosively zero-sum characterization of a cover <em>that benefited Chapman, by her own account</em> .在我看来，查普曼，一个独特且才华横溢的人，写了《快车》，而不是黑人社区，或酷儿社区，或包含所有黑人女性艺术家的集体。对我来说，如果库姆斯找到一位酷儿黑人女性并说：“我翻唱了一首与你肤色和性取向相同的人的歌曲；想和我一起巡演吗？”我会欢呼成功的乡村音乐家为使他们的流派多样化而做出的积极努力，但上面引用的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://bigthink.com/the-present/racecraft-racism/">赛车手艺</a>与一个不同种族的人在一个受人爱戴的社区中平等的世界是不相容的，而不是“其他人”。与此同时，我很欣赏黑奥普里的霍莉正在努力做她认为的好事，我祝愿她的大部分项目取得成功，尤其是因为我很高兴看到第一位黑人乡村女明星。<br><br><em>这就是今天的全部内容——下周见。</em><br><br><em>感谢您的贡献。我读了你发来的每一封信。提交电子邮件即表示您同意我们在新闻通讯和我们的网站上部分或全部使用该电子邮件。除非您的初始注释中另有要求，否则发布的反馈可能包括作者的全名、城市和州，并且可能会根据长度和清晰度进行编辑。</em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 23 Jul 2023 14:33:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/why-is-tracy-chapman-at-the-center-of-a-country-music-controversy/674794/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/why-is-tracy-chapman-at-the-center-of-a-country-music-controversy/674794/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Great PowerPoint Panic of 2003]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>二十年前，企业演示软件被称为“理性的终结”。为什么？ <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/8o43uZBUeyWGPeMdX_NS8ALYxAw=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/powerpoint_version_/original.jpg" alt="带有螺旋圆圈的演示屏幕" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>本·科特/大西洋月刊；资料来源：盖蒂</figcaption></figure><span class="smallcaps">新媒体技术</span>将使我们变得愚蠢，将所有的人际互动减少为推销。它会腐蚀我们的思想，降低沟通效率，浪费我们的时间。正如一位著名艺术家<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://personal.utdallas.edu/~dxt023000/courses/6331/readings/Byrne-Powerpoint.pdf">所说</a>，它的突然兴起并通过商业、政府和教育迅速传播，预示着“理性的终结”，无论好坏。最终，它甚至会因国家电视台现场直播七名美国人的死亡而受到指责。那是 2003 年，美国人对 Microsoft PowerPoint 所带来的改变世界的风险感到惊慌失措。<br><br>苏格拉底曾经<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://www.gutenberg.org/files/1636/1636-h/1636-h.htm#2H_4_0002">警告说</a>，书面文字会削弱我们的记忆力。文艺复兴时期的博学家康拉德·盖斯纳警告说，印刷机会让我们淹没在“令人困惑和有害的大量书籍中”。此后的几代人都担心其他新技术——广播、电视、视频游戏——会腐蚀我们孩子的大脑。仅在过去的 15 年里，这本杂志就对<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2008/07/is-google-making-us-stupid/306868/">谷歌</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2017/09/has-the-smartphone-destroyed-a-generation/534198/">智能手机</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/05/social-media-democracy-trust-babel/629369/">社交媒体</a>敲响了警钟。其中一些批评似乎已经过时了。其他人则不太好。但其中隐藏着一种最高级别的技术恐慌，这种恐惧如今几乎已被完全遗忘：人们相信 PowerPoint——Office 软件套件中最令人疲惫不堪的成员，催眠会议的通用转喻——可能是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wired.com/2003/09/ppt2/">邪恶的</a>。<br><br>二十年后，“幻灯片大恐慌”读起来既是一场闹剧，又是一场悲剧。当时，社交媒体时代已经来临：MySpace 和 LinkedIn 刚刚成立，而 Facebook 的推出也只有几个月的时间。但即使<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/12/facebook-doomsday-machine/617384/">极化机器</a>运转起来，我们仍然关注<em>要点</em>所带来的生存威胁。我们是否只是错过了目标？或者，尽管今天看起来很荒谬，但我们是在做某件事吗？<br><br> 2003 年 2 月 1 日早上，<span class="smallcaps">距离着陆还有 16 分钟</span>，哥伦比亚号航天飞机在无云的东德克萨斯天空中解体。机上七名宇航员全部遇难。当破碎的航天飞机碎片冲向地球时，在现场电视观众看来，它就像一群流星。<br><br>美国宇航局事故调查委员会的一份报告确定，这场灾难的直接<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.britannica.com/event/Columbia-disaster">原因</a>是一块绝缘泡沫在升空后不久就松动并损坏了航天飞机的左翼。但报告还指出了一个不那么直接、更令人惊讶的罪魁祸首。早在哥伦比亚号尝试重返大气层之前，工程师们就已经知道并不恰当地低估了机翼的损坏情况，但他们分析中的缺陷被隐藏在向美国宇航局官员展示的一系列晦涩难懂、内容过多的计算机演示幻灯片中。报告指出：“很容易理解高级管理人员阅读这张 PowerPoint 幻灯片却没有意识到它解决的是危及生命的情况。”随后继续说道：“董事会认为普遍使用 PowerPoint 简报幻灯片而不是技术论文来说明 NASA 的技术沟通方法存在问题。”<br><br> PowerPoint 当时并不是一项新技术，但它最近已变得无处不在。 1987年，该节目首次发布时，销量为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=RC_5OCQQJ7YC">4万份</a>。十年后，销量达到<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.webcitation.org/6bxj2eryp?url=https://filetea.me/t1sEVBHlotISPCAVUKpeg2F5A">400万张</a>。到 2000 年代初期，PowerPoint 已经占据了演示软件市场 95% 的份额，它对美国人说话和思考方式日益增长的影响已经引起了批评。伊恩·帕克 (Ian Parker) 2001 年在<em>《纽约客》</em>上发表的一篇<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2001/05/28/absolute-powerpoint">专题文章</a>认为，该软件“可以帮助您提出案例，但它也提出自己的案例：关于如何组织信息、组织多少信息、如何看待世界。” “互联网之父”之一温特·瑟夫 (Vint Cerf) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.edwardtufte.com/bboard/q-and-a-fetch-msg?msg_id=0000iF">打趣</a>道，“权力会腐败，而 PowerPoint 绝对会腐败。”<br><br>到 2003 年初， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.amazon.com/Death-Powerpoint-Presentation-Audience-Effective/dp/0964888254"><em>“PowerPoint 带来的死亡”</em></a>这个词已经真正进入了流行词汇。耶鲁大学的统计学家爱德华·塔夫特（Edward Tufte）是第一个从字面上理解这一点的人：那年春天，塔夫特发表了一篇猛烈的猛烈抨击，题为<em>《PowerPoint 的认知风格》</em> ，其中包括他对该软件在最近的哥伦比亚灾难中所扮演的角色的分析。它的封面是塔夫特自己设计的政治漫画，展示了一张军队营的照片，它们在布达佩斯市中心的约瑟夫·斯大林的巨型雕像前排成完美的纵队。一名士兵嘴里冒出一个对话气泡：“没有像斯大林的子弹清单那样的子弹清单！”另一个人喊道：“但是为什么要大声朗读每张幻灯片呢？”就连斯大林也会说：“следующий слайд，”他说，“请下一张幻灯片。”<br><br>该小册子的核心论点借鉴了马歇尔·麦克卢汉的观点，即传播媒介影响传播的实质内容，而 PowerPoint 作为媒介具有令人困惑、简化的效果。它不一定会产生含糊、懒惰的表述，但它确实容纳了甚至有时甚至掩盖了它们——这可能会带来致命的后果。这正是塔夫特在哥伦比亚工程师的幻灯片中看到的。 “PP 的认知风格影响了分析，”他在 NASA 调查报告得出非常相似的结论前几个月宣称。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2013/11/the-gettysburg-address-as-a-powerpoint/281636/">阅读：葛底斯堡演说作为幻灯片</a><br><br>尽管塔夫特的立场很激进，但人们还是认真对待他。当时他已经作为公共知识分子而闻名：他的信息设计一日游课程与其说是巡回演讲，不如说是摇滚之旅。每次会议都有数百人挤进酒店的宴会厅。 “他们来听爱德华·R·塔夫特的演讲，”一位作家当时<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.edwardtufte.com/tufte/advocate_1099">评论道</a>，“就像古希腊人听苏格拉底或未来的超验主义者开辟了通向 19 世纪协和的道路一样。”因此，当“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/1998/03/30/business/the-da-vinci-of-data.html">数据界的达芬奇</a>”决定参与即将被称为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newspapers.com/image/114249178/">PowerPoint 辩论</a>”的活动时，人们纷纷倾听。<br><br> <em>《连线》杂志</em>2003 年 9 月摘录了他的小册子，标题为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wired.com/2003/09/ppt2/">PowerPoint 是邪恶的</a>”。几个月后， <em>《纽约时报》杂志</em>将 Tufte 的评价纳入其年度最有趣、最重要的想法的回顾中，总结为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2003/12/14/magazine/2003-the-3rd-annual-year-in-ideas-powerpoint-makes-you-dumb.html">PowerPoint 让你变得愚蠢</a>”。 “也许 PowerPoint 特别适合我们这个混乱的现代时代，”该条目写道，并指出<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/09/politics/powell-calls-his-un-speech-a-lasting-blot-on-his-record.html">科林·鲍威尔</a>刚刚<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20031118030817/http:/www.state.gov/documents/organization/17434.pdf">使用该软件</a>向联合国提交了伊拉克大规模杀伤性武器的证据。<br><br>几页上是该杂志令人兴奋的新想法列表中的另一个值得注意的条目： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2003/12/14/magazine/2003-the-3rd-annual-year-in-ideas-social-networks.html">社交网络</a>。尽管 PowerPoint 与<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/17/magazine/faith-certainty-and-the-presidency-of-george-w-bush.html">现实扭曲</a>和美国人很快称之为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/17/magazine/17FOB-onlanguage-t.html">真实性</a>”的兴起联系在一起，但 Friendster、LinkedIn 和其他此类网络仍然没有定论。文章称，也许通过增强社会联系，他们可以减轻我们“深刻的民族孤独感”。也许他们只会“进一步将生活分裂成不同的领域——线上和线下。”或者也许它们不会那么具有变革性——至少与像 PowerPoint 这样普遍且有影响力的技术相比是这样。<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">Tufte 现年 81 岁</span>，早已退休。根据他的最终统计，“ET 巡回演唱会”已经结束，共有 328,001 名参加者。这些天，他主要从事<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.edwardtufte.com/tufte/sculpture">雕塑工作</a>。但他仍然是他自己：他仍然讨厌 PowerPoint。他仍然从称其为“PP”中获得了幼儿园孩子的喜悦。如果您访问 edwardtufte.com，您仍然可以以 14 美元的价格购买海报形式的斯大林漫画。<br><br> In May, I emailed Tufte to ask how he thought his critique of PowerPoint had aged.一如往常，他用专门为我编译的 16 页 PDF 进行了回答，其中包括他的书的摘录以及一些关于这些书的简介。他最终同意通过电话交谈，但我给他的第一个电话转到了语音信箱。 “在这片时间消失的土地上，外星人是不存在的，”他在电影预告片戏剧性的传出信息中咒语道。 “沟通的关键是语音信箱。或者短信。做吧！<em>嘟嘟</em>。<br><br>当我最终到达 ET 时，我问他，经过 20 年的稳定使用，PowerPoint 是否真的让我们变得愚蠢了。 “我不知道，”他说。 “我到过另一个星球。我现在是一名艺术家。”他接着说，从某种意义上说，他是最不该问的人，因为自 2003 年以来，没有人敢向他展示 PowerPoint 演示文稿。他还声称自己没有“记分”，但他知道——并且很感激——最近<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.workingbackwards.com/">有消息称</a>，他的工作帮助激励杰夫·贝佐斯禁止亚马逊高级管理人员使用 PowerPoint。<br><br>贝佐斯并不是唯一一个以塔夫特的方式看待事情的人。史蒂夫·乔布斯还禁止在某些公司会议上使用 PowerPoint。 2010 年在北卡罗来纳州举行的一次军事会议上，前国家安全顾问、时任陆军将军的 HR 麦克马斯特 (HR McMaster) 将 PowerPoint 描述为一种内部威胁；他曾在 2005 年袭击伊拉克城市塔尔阿法尔期间禁止使用它。“PowerPoint 让我们变得愚蠢，”詹姆斯·马蒂斯 (James Mattis) 将军在同一次会议上说道。 2011 年，瑞士的一位前软件工程师组建了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.anti-powerpoint-party.com/">反 PowerPoint 党</a>，这是一个（某种意义上）真正致力于对抗幻灯片暴政的政党。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2008/07/is-google-making-us-stupid/306868/">阅读：谷歌让我们变得愚蠢吗？</a><br><br>塔夫特的文章也面临着一些批评。一些人指责他为了提高他的课程出勤率而制造争议。其他人则表示，他犯了一个错误，因为他将该软件与用户的习惯混淆了。 “任何对 PowerPoint 的普遍反对都是愚蠢的，”哈佛大学心理学家史蒂文·平克 (Steven Pinker) 2009 年对<em>《</em><em>华尔街日报》</em> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204619004574318473921093400">表示</a>。“这就像谴责讲座一样——在糟糕的 PowerPoint 演示出现之前，还有糟糕的有脚本的讲座、无脚本的讲座、幻灯片、粉笔演讲等等。”长期担任麦肯锡商业视觉演示总监的吉恩·泽拉兹尼 (Gene Zelazny) 将塔夫特的论点<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.robertgaskins.com/files/five-experts-dispute-edward-tufte-on-powerpoint-sociable-media-cliff-atkinson.htm">总结</a>为“将司机造成的事故归咎于汽车”。<br><br>这种比较的问题在于，我们的交通系统<em>确实</em>对美国每年发生的 30,000 至 40,000 起车祸死亡负有一定责任，因为它让司机陷入了造成事故的境地。塔夫特告诉我，PowerPoint 也有类似的效果，它会积极促进糟糕的演示。 “这对演讲者来说很方便，”他说，“但对观众和内容来说却很不方便，而且有害。”<br><br>但如果所有这些糟糕的演讲真的导致了广泛的社会弊病，那么证据就很难找到。一些科学家试图对所谓的 PowerPoint 效应进行<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/228864609_The_PowerPoint_Presentation_and_Its_Corollaries_How_Genres_Shape_Communicative_Action_in_Organizations">正式</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/20868864">衡量</a>，询问该软件是否真的影响我们处理信息的能力。瑞士圣加仑大学创意与设计教授塞巴斯蒂安·科恩巴赫 (Sebastian Kernbach) 与人合着了多篇综合这些文献的评论。他告诉我，总体而言，研究表明塔夫特的观点部分正确，部分错误。 PowerPoint 似乎并没有让我们变得愚蠢——例如，没有证据表明使用它的人的信息保留率较低或普遍认知能力下降——但它确实强加了一系列关于信息应该如何传达的假设：松散地、以要点的形式，并由演示者向被动听众的观众传达。科恩巴赫说，这些假设甚至重塑了幻灯片时代的物理环境：研讨会桌曾经被配置为圆形，但在 PowerPoint 之后已被弯曲成 U 形以容纳演示者。<br><br>当我与科恩巴赫交谈时，他正在准备向一家大型政府组织的一群员工进行关于视觉思维的不同方法的演讲。 He said he planned to use a flip chart, draw on blank slides like a whiteboard, and perhaps even have audience members do some drawing of their own.但他也准备使用常规的旧 PowerPoint 幻灯片。他告诉我，这样做将为他的听众“标志着准备和专业精神”。该组织是美国宇航局。<br><br>美国航天局<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/kathrynlueders_lgbtq_vendor_equity_forum_presentation.pptx">仍然使用</a>PowerPoint 这一事实并不令人意外。尽管它引起了媒体的强烈反对，激起了亿万富翁的愤怒，并在军队内部引起了红色警报，但企业演示的盛行仍在继续。微软 PowerPoint 产品副总裁 Shawn Villaron 表示，该程序的每月用户数量比以往任何时候都多，已达数亿。如果说有什么不同的话，那就是它的用例已经激增。封锁期间，人们在 Zoom 上举办<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.elitedaily.com/p/heres-how-to-host-a-powerpoint-party-for-a-creative-get-together-22793116">PowerPoint 派对</a>。现在，当孩子们想养一只小狗、退出足球或参加 Niall Horan 见面会时，他们可以为父母<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/20/style/kids-who-use-powerpoint-to-ask-for-things.html">做 PowerPoint 演示</a>。如果 PowerPoint 是邪恶的，那么邪恶就统治了世界。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">至少从表面上看</span>，PowerPoint 让我们变得愚蠢的想法看起来像是教科书上误导性的技术末日论案例。当我要求塔夫特重新审视他的批评时，他表示反对，但在后来的谈话中，我更直接地向他询问了这个问题：他自己对一项新技术的批评是否有可能没有达到目标，就像过去许多其他人所做的那样？对 PowerPoint 的担忧与对印刷机或<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://www.collisiondetection.net/mt/archives/2010/12/will_the_word_p.php">文字处理器</a>的担忧有什么不同吗？<br><br>在我把这个想法说完之前，他插嘴了。他明显恼怒地说道，这个问题无法回答。 “我不做大的思考，大的废话，”他告诉我。 “我就在战壕里，正在进行沟通。”我认为他的意思是他不参与任何形式的远程抽象历史思考。<br><br>我尝试缩小问题范围。我说，今天对社交媒体的担忧与 PowerPoint 的批评有一定的相似之处。两者都归结为一种担忧，即新媒体技术重视形式而不是实质，它们的设计目的是吸引我们的注意力而不是传达真理，而且它们让我们变得愚蠢。有没有可能——有没有可能——塔夫特做出了正确的批评，但却批评了错误的技术？他没有这样的感觉。他说，PowerPoint 和社交媒体之间的比较是“挥手、胡说和机会主义”。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/07/social-media-harm-facebook-meta-response/670975/">阅读：是的，社交媒体确实正在破坏民主</a><br><br>尽管有这样的驳回，我们还是很容易会产生反事实，并想知道如果塔夫特和我们其他人早在 2003 年就担心社交媒体而不是演示软件，事情会如何发展。也许一本关于<em>Friendster 认知风格的</em>及时小册子或<em>断言</em>“LinkedIn 是邪恶的”的《连线》头条会改变历史的进程。如果过去几年社交媒体的强烈抵制从一开始就存在，也许 Facebook 永远不会成长为现在这样的庞然大物，这个国家也永远不会变得如此绝望的分裂。<br><br>或者也可能什么都不会改变。无论他们的时机如何，也无论他们的适应性如何，对新媒体的担忧似乎很少产生影响。反对意见遭到压制。新技术占据了主导地位。多年后，当我们回顾过去并想，<em>我们如此不安是多么奇怪</em>，这项技术的影响很可能是看不见的。<br><br>书面文字是否摧毁了我们的记忆？广播是否缩短了我们的注意力范围？ PowerPoint 是否让我们变成了企业官僚？如果这些创新确实改变了我们的思维方式，那么我们就会用改变的思维来衡量它们的影响。这些批评要么是错误的，要么是正确的，以至于我们无法再区分。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 23 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/power-point-evil-tufte-history/674797/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/power-point-evil-tufte-history/674797/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Liberal Suburbs Have Their Own Border Wall]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>富裕的蓝色城镇的居民谈论包容性，但他们的法律却恰恰相反。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/uIM3883HZFkQO372hq4ooRe3_DI=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/SuburbHipocracy/original.png" alt="带刺铁丝栅栏的插图" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Paul Spella / The Atlantic.资料来源：盖蒂； Shutterstock.</figcaption></figure>纽约市郊区斯卡斯代尔位于纽约州威彻斯特县，是美国<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/scarsdale-new-york-east-coast-richest-town-photo-tour-2019-3">最富有的</a>社区之一，其居民确实是自由派。 2020 年，<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.politico.com/2020-election/results/new-york/">四分之三</a>的斯卡斯代尔选民将选票投给了乔·拜登，而不是唐纳德·特朗普。人们可以有把握地推测，很少有斯卡斯代尔居民是特朗普在墨西哥边境修建隔离墙的热心支持者。但他们中的许多人支持一种不太明显的隔离墙，这种隔离墙是根据分区法规建立的，禁止多户住宅，并将非富人（其中许多是有色人种）排除在社区之外。<br><br>在全国范围内，许多优秀的白人自由主义者，他们购买<em>《白人脆弱性》</em>的副本并谴责美国最高法院终止平权行动，每天晚上都睡在专属郊区，这些郊区通过政府法令对经济（从而种族）隔离进行社会设计。高档城市和较贫困的邻居之间的巨大不平等并不是凭空出现的；它们在很大程度上是法律的产物，这些法律很难与许多受过高等教育的深蓝色郊区草坪上的包容性<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2021/10/29/arts/in-this-house-yard-signs.html">“在这所房子里，我们相信”的标志相一致</a>。<br><br>在世纪基金会的一份<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tcf.org/content/report/how-zoning-drives-educational-inequality-the-case-of-westchester-county/">新报告</a>中，我将斯卡斯代尔与另一个韦斯特切斯特县郊区切斯特港进行了对比，后者仅距八英里，但人口统计数据却截然不同。斯卡斯代尔的家庭收入中位数超过<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/scarsdalevillagenewyork/PST045222">25 万美元</a>，几乎是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/portchestervillagenewyork/PST045222">切斯特港</a>的三倍，拥有大学学位的居民比例也是如此。切斯特港四分之三的小学生有资格在学校享受免费或减价餐，而斯卡斯代尔的学生则只有零。在斯卡斯代尔，87% 的居民是非西班牙裔白人或亚裔美国人，而切斯特港 69% 的居民是黑人或西班牙裔。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/09/black-families-leaving-cities-suburbs/671331/">耶路撒冷德姆萨斯：是什么导致了黑人的逃亡？</a><br><br>在斯卡斯代尔的绝大多数土地上，建造除单户住宅以外的任何东西都是非法的。根据纽约大学弗曼中心为该报告收集的数据，斯卡斯代尔的地块中只有 0.2% 的建筑被归类为两户或三户住宅或公寓。相比之下，切斯特港大约一半的土地允许建造多户住宅。从 2014 年到 2021 年，切斯特港批准的新住房单元中有 41% 是多户住宅。 In Scarsdale, none of the 218 units permitted were for a multifamily home.当斯卡斯代尔提议建造多户住宅时，居民提出了许多反对意见，其中许多是虚假的。例如，一些人反对公寓，理由是多户住宅会导致学校过度拥挤，尽管数据显示近年来斯卡斯代尔村的入学率一直在下降。<br><br>事实上，许多为孩子寻求更好生活的人都希望有机会搬到斯卡斯代尔。在我为我的新书<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/excluded-how-snob-zoning-nimbyism-and-class-bias-build-the-walls-we-don-t-see-richard-d-kahlenberg/9781541701465?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>《排除：势利分区、邻避主义和阶级偏见如何筑起我们看不到的围墙》</em></a>进行的采访中，来自全国各地的低薪单亲母亲反复表达了她们希望为孩子提供更好的学校的愿望。<br><br>正如我在世纪基金会报告中指出的那样，2020 年斯卡斯代尔在每个学生上的支出比切斯特港多了近 5,500 美元，并且学生与教师的比例较低。 2019 年，切斯特港 32% 的学生英语成绩达到年级水平，而斯卡斯代尔的这一比例为 87%，差距高达 55 个百分点。在数学方面，切斯特港学生有 35% 的成绩达到年级水平，而斯卡斯代尔学生的这一比例为 90%，差距也为 55 分。研究<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tcf.org/content/report/housing-policy-school-policy-economically-integrative-housing-promotes-academic-success-montgomery-county-maryland/">表明</a>，当低收入学生有机会进入贫困程度较低的学校时，他们可以在五到七年的时间内将与中产阶级同龄人在数学方面的成绩差距缩小一半，在阅读方面的成绩差距缩小三分之一。他们只是很少有选择。<br><br>电视摄像机有助于描绘在边境被拒之门外的移民家庭的困境，但它们并没有捕捉到切斯特港等地的工薪阶层家庭被排除在斯卡斯代尔等地机会较高的公立学校之外的情况，这些学校禁止建造弱势家庭能够负担得起的房屋类型。尽管斯卡斯代尔的家长可能会试图通过支持切斯特港等地增加国家教育支出来调和排斥与他们的政治自由主义之间的关系， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tcf.org/content/report/bold-agenda-school-integration/">但人们发现</a>学校的经济一体化比“分开但平等”的补偿性支出方法更有效。<br><br>通过限制住房供应，斯卡斯代尔的分区法以及纽约市其他郊区的类似规则也人为推高了大都市区的房价。今年早些时候，纽约州州长凯西·霍赫尔 (Kathy Hochul) 提出了《纽约住房契约》(New York Housing Compact)，该契约将为威彻斯特县等州下城市制定每三年将住房供应量增加 3% 的目标。如果社区未能实现这些目标，州政府将要求市政当局为住房许可证申请人提供快速审批流程。此外，南部地区需要重新规划，以在通勤铁路和地铁站半英里范围内增加住房。目前，在斯卡斯代尔，火车站附近的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wshu.org/long-island-news/2023-02-06/hochul-wants-to-build-hundreds-of-thousands-of-homes-near-train-stations">几乎所有土地都</a>被划为包含单户住宅的大片土地。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/06/zoning-housing-affordability-nimby-parking-houston/661289/">M. Nolan Gray：取消分区</a><br><br>然而，尽管“在我家后院”的改革在加利福尼亚州、俄勒冈州以及明尼阿波利斯和夏洛特等城市获得了关注，自由派的纽约州立法机构在民选官员和来自富裕的自由派郊区的公民领袖的帮助下，深化了温和的民主党州长的住房议程。斯卡斯代尔民主党人艾米·波林 (Amy Paulin) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/03/29/nyregion/nyc-suburbs-homes-hochul.html">告诉<em>《纽约时报》</em></a> ，霍赫尔的“提议将以一种没有意义的方式改变我们县的复杂性。”与此同时，威彻斯特县州参议院民主党领袖安德里亚·斯图尔特-考辛斯(Andrea Stewart-Cousins)拒绝了霍赫尔的计划，并呼吁采取财政激励措施，鼓励社区自愿允许提供更多住房。<br><br>富裕的保守地区也对新住房设置了障碍，但自由地区的情况通常更糟。布鲁金斯学会研究员珍妮·舒茨 (Jenny Schuetz) 在 2022 年撰文<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.brookings.edu/books/fixer-upper/">指出</a>，“经济学家和城市规划者数十年来对分区的潜心研究，已经就美国哪些地方拥有严格的土地使用法规达成了高度共识，无论衡量分区的方法如何。”她认为，“过度限制性的分区在西海岸和从华盛顿特区到波士顿的东北走廊地区最为普遍，也存在问题。”这些地区“在国家、州和地方选举中严重倾向于民主党”。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0094119010000720">研究</a>各州（例如加利福尼亚州）内分区的严格性的研究发现，限制性最强的分区出现在政治上较为自由的社区。<br><br>在波士顿郊区马萨诸塞州列克星敦，家庭收入中位数为 203,000 美元，选民支持拜登的比例为 81% 对 17%，排斥之墙非常陡峭。想要建造三层公寓的开发商需要至少 15,500 英尺的土地——是邻近沃尔瑟姆最小地块面积的两倍以上（收入中位数为 103,000 美元）。据波士顿大学三名研究人员统计，沃尔瑟姆的建筑商必须遵守 17 项规定，而列克星敦的建筑商则面临 34 项规定。<br><br>新泽西州普林斯顿的选民以六比一的优势支持拜登，政治学家奥马尔·瓦索（Omar Wasow） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2020/08/01/us/white-liberals-hypocrisy-race-blake/index.html">尖刻地观察到</a>，“普林斯顿镇的一些人会在自家前草坪上挂上“黑人生命也是命”的标语，并挂上写着‘我们爱我们的穆斯林邻居’的标语，但反对改变分区政策，即每栋房子必须拥有一英亩半的土地。”他继续说：“这意味着，‘我们爱我们的穆斯林邻居，只要他们是百万富翁。’”（拥有少量富有的有色人种邻居可能会让享有特权的白人房主相信这个制度是公正的。）<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/05/zoning-laws-nuclear-modern-family-definition/674117/">阅读：与朋友同住在技术上是非法的</a><br><br>富裕郊区保持排他性的努力可能会失败。 2019 年 6 月，俄勒冈州成为第一个在全州<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2019/07/01/737798440/oregon-legislature-votes-to-essentially-ban-single-family-zoning">范围内颁布虚拟单户住宅分区条例</a>的州。这项改革的发生只是因为农村共和党人往往对政府土地使用法规（以及自由派精英）持怀疑态度，他们与城市民主党人一起击败了富裕的郊区利益集团。 2021 年 9 月，加利福尼亚州的一个类似联盟重复了这一壮举，将全州范围内的复式住宅<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2021/08/26/business/california-duplex-senate-bill-9.html">合法化</a>，并允许人们细分地块，这可能意味着以前是单户住宅的地块上可以有多达四套住宅。一位住房专家<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2021/10/08/business/economy/california-housing.html">告诉《<em>泰晤士报》</em></a> ，此类法律“开放了基本上被隔离的整个社区”。<br><br>对于一个几十年来邻避部队可靠地赢得政治斗争的国家来说，此类法律的通过是一个惊人的发展。它表明，持续了这么长时间并造成如此大破坏的分区墙正变得越来越难以防御。在修剪整齐的草坪上张贴欢迎标语是不够的。如果富裕的自由派郊区居民相信其他人应该有机会改善自己的生活，那么他们能做的最重要的事情就是允许中等收入的家庭进入他们的城镇。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 23 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/wealthy-liberal-suburbs-economic-segregation-scarsdale/674792/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/wealthy-liberal-suburbs-economic-segregation-scarsdale/674792/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Wrong-Apartment Problem]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Why a good economy feels so bad <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/P0ehptGO9OM3LXE_iAs36pWlHiY=/0x0:2500x1406/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/Economy_1/original.png" alt="image of a figure on an upward arrow" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Ben Hickey</figcaption></figure> Dr. Dre on the radio, <i>The Matrix</i> on the big screen, <i>The Sopranos</i> on TV: The year 1999 was wonderful for many reasons, including economic ones.<br><br> That year, the median household income rose to a record level, a watermark that held for nearly two decades. (The average American family was poorer when Donald Trump was running for office than when Bill Clinton left office.) Wages were growing across the board—all kinds of workers were getting consistent raises. Productivity growth <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/PRS85006092">was strong</a> . Wealth inequality was <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/WFRBST01134">holding steady</a> and far lower <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/WFRBST01134">than it is today</a> . The <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.povertycenter.columbia.edu/historical-spm-data">poverty rate</a> hit its lowest point in years.<br><br> I could go on and on with the hard statistics: The share of workers with a college degree was <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.statista.com/statistics/184260/educational-attainment-in-the-us/#:~:text=In%202020%2C%20about%2037.9%20percent,population%20had%20graduated%20from%20college.">climbing</a> . The homeownership rate was <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/RHORUSQ156N">booming</a> . The stock market, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.marketwatch.com/investing/index/spx">booming</a> . Consumer confidence was the highest it has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tradingeconomics.com/united-states/consumer-confidence#:~:text=Consumer%20Confidence%20in%20the%20United,points%20in%20June%20of%202022.">ever been</a> . The share of people employed was the highest it has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/EMRATIO">ever been</a> . Investor optimism was the highest it has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.gallup.com/poll/352334/inflation-concerns-temper-investor-optimism.aspx">ever been</a> . The share of Americans saying the country was going in the right direction—also the highest it has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.gallup.com/poll/1669/general-mood-country.aspx">ever been</a> .<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/economics-inequality-piketty-milanovic/674702/">Yascha Mounk: Goodbye to the prophets of doom</a><br><br> Things just <i>felt</i> like they were going well and getting better. High-quality televisions were becoming ubiquitous; cellphones were beginning to replace pagers. The share of homes with a computer and an internet hookup <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/content/dam/Census/library/publications/2018/acs/ACS-39.pdf">was exploding</a> , and the web was promising to change everything.<br><br> Now: Earwormy TikTok blips on the radio, warmed-over superheroes on the big screen (at least until <i>Barbenheimer</i> ), Peak TV drowning us in okay content: 2023 is blah for many reasons. Roughly half the country thinks we&#39;re in a recession or about to be in one. Consumer confidence is down, as is investor sentiment. Inflation is weighing on American families.<br><br> But I&#39;m here to tell you that this is the best economy ever. Really. This year&#39;s economy has now outpaced that of 1999, the previous best on record. It is growing more equitably than it has in years. American families are more financially secure and wealthier than they ever have been. Things are going great, I swear.<br><br> The labor market is flourishing, and not just for rich folks for once. The unemployment rate is at its lowest level in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/UNRATE">60 years</a> —jobs are more plentiful than they have been <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/JTSJOR">in a generation</a> . Competition for workers has not only pushed earnings up—median household income is sitting near its <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/MEHOINUSA672N">brand-new high</a> , one that is $6,000 higher than it was in the late 1990s. It has also pushed earnings up more for the lowest-paid workers than the highest-paid workers. The past three years have erased a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nber.org/system/files/working_papers/w31010/w31010.pdf">quarter of the run-up</a> in wage inequality created in the past four decades. Real wages for the lowest-paid workers are growing faster than they have since the 1960s. The country&#39;s wage structure is getting more equal, not less.<br><br> Arindrajit Dube, a labor economist studying this “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nber.org/papers/w31010">unexpected</a> ” phenomenon, told me that the country&#39;s “job ladder” had broken about 20 years ago: Workers in crappy jobs found themselves stuck in those crappy jobs, unable to move up. “Starting around 2018 or 2019, you start to see the tight labor market bring back some health and dynamism,” he told me. “People are making more changes. The Great Resignation, the Great Reshuffle, whatever you want to call it—it means the market is working better. And it&#39;s allowing people to leave jobs that are really bad.” As a result, workers report feeling <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.conference-board.org/research/job-satisfaction/US-worker-satisfaction-continues-to-increase">more satisfied</a> with their jobs now than at any point since the 1980s, and 4 million more people have full-time jobs (and 1.6 million fewer people have <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/juliaonjobs/status/1678747214594678784">part-time jobs</a> ) than before the pandemic.<br><br> Improvements in earnings, along with the stimulus payments the government made during the pandemic, have helped lift millions of families out of poverty. The child-poverty rate has fallen from 12.5 percent to just 5.2 percent over the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/content/dam/Census/library/publications/2022/demo/p60-277.pdf">past three years</a> . That&#39;s the lowest level ever recorded. The share of people living in deep poverty and near-poverty has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/content/dam/Census/library/publications/2022/demo/p60-277.pdf">declined, too</a> , and food insecurity is at its <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ers.usda.gov/data-products/ag-and-food-statistics-charting-the-essentials/food-security-and-nutrition-assistance/#:~:text=In%202021%2C%2089.8%20percent%20of,had%20very%20low%20food%20security.">lowest-ever rate</a> .<br><br> Bigger paychecks are helping middle-class families buy houses and build wealth. The homeownership rate was increasing faster <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nar.realtor/newsroom/u-s-homeownership-rate-experiences-largest-annual-increase-on-record-though-black-homeownership-remains-lower-than-decade-ago">than it ever had</a> , until interest rates spiked a year ago; families in the lower half of the income distribution are more likely to own their homes now than at any point <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/housing/hvs/data/histtabs.html">since the real-estate bubble</a> burst in 2006. Most Millennials own <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.apartmentlist.com/research/millennial-homeownership-2023">property</a> ; the generation is starting to catch up with Gen Xers and Boomers in terms of net worth and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.jchs.harvard.edu/blog/surge-household-growth-and-what-it-suggests-about-future-housing-demand">household formation</a> .<br><br> The economy has also delivered extraordinary gains for Black Americans. The jobless rate for Black workers is near <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/LNS14000006">a historic low</a> , and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/LNS14000006#0">the gap between</a> the unemployment rate for white workers and Black workers is the smallest it has ever been. Black workers&#39; earnings are <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/LEU0252884600Q">increasing rapidly</a> too.<br><br> Measured in all sorts of more esoteric ways, American families are doing the best they ever have. The delinquency rate on loans is the lowest it <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/DRALACBN">has ever been</a> . Real disposable income is the highest it has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/A229RX0A048NBEA">ever been</a> . The personal-bankruptcy rate is at an <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://finmasters.com/personal-bankruptcy-statistics/#gref">all-time low</a> .<br><br> So we have to ask: Why aren&#39;t we partying like it&#39;s 1999?<br><br> The most immediate answer is inflation. It is not only sapping folks&#39; paychecks (though earnings and disposable income are still up in inflation-adjusted terms). People just hate having to do mental math every time they fill up their tank or hit the grocery store. And consumers tend not to notice when things get better as opposed to worse: Inflation has cooled off considerably, and the prices of eggs, gas, used cars, plane tickets, and dozens of other common <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bls.gov/news.release/cpi.nr0.htm">consumer goods</a> are falling, but that fact has not seeped in for <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.gallup.com/poll/1675/most-important-problem.aspx">many families</a> .<br><br> Then there is something I like to call the Wrong-Apartment Problem. The country&#39;s big cities have added far too few housing units over the past few decades; now even rural areas have shortages. By <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/11/us-housing-gap-cost-affordability-big-cities/672184/">one estimate</a> , roughly half of Americans would live somewhere different if supply met demand; New York would be eight times as big as it is now, and San Francisco five times as big. Renters <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.anderson.ucla.edu/documents/areas/ctr/ziman/ConfAfford2015_Albouy-Ehrlich-Liu_Housing-Demand-Expenditures2_09.09.15.pdf">spend</a> a larger share of their income on housing than they did in 1999, and rents <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.moodys.com/web/en/us/about/insights/data-stories/us-rental-housing-affordability.html">have grown</a> by 135 percent, whereas average incomes have grown just 77 percent. The country has an <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/great-affordability-crisis-breaking-america/606046/">affordability crisis</a> , with health care, child care, and rent eating up huge shares of family budgets.<br><br> Yet these statistics still <i>underplay</i> just how bad the situation is. People don&#39;t spend what they can&#39;t afford, and pretty much nobody can afford what they want anymore. Yes, we have more income, more disposable cash, and a better standard of living than at any other point in our history. But millions of us can&#39;t live in the neighborhoods we want. We&#39;re stuck in too-small, too-far-away accommodations, giving up on the dream of having a second bathroom or a third kid. This is why you get all the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/LifesNotFoehr/status/1676341223349534721">social-media nostalgia</a> for the economic conditions of the 1950s, when many Americans still lacked <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/data/tables/time-series/dec/coh-plumbing.html">indoor plumbing</a> , but at least could live in Brooklyn or Somerville or San Francisco on a reasonable salary. We&#39;re all stuck in the Wrong Apartment.<br><br> A third major element is inequality. Although lower-income Americans have begun narrowing the gap, that&#39;s a very recent phenomenon. And the incomes of the very richest are <i>still</i> rising faster than anybody else&#39;s. Even if living standards are improving, the sense that the gains aren&#39;t being equally shared is noxious to our polity.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/bidenomics-economic-pessimism/674701/">James Surowiecki: The bad-vibes economy</a><br><br> The political and media environments are surely factors as well. Today&#39;s intense polarization pushes folks to hate the economy if they hate the president and love the economy if they love the president, meaning that Republicans just aren&#39;t happy right now. “Partisan bias exerts a significant influence on survey measures of economic expectations, and this bias is increasing,” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://direct.mit.edu/rest/article/105/3/493/100979/Partisan-Bias-Economic-Expectations-and-Household">new research finds</a> . Switch on the TV, and the world is a bummer, too: the climate catastrophe, war in Europe, threats to democracy at home, social-media frying our brains and ruining <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/12/the-sex-recession/573949/">sex</a> and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://slate.com/culture/2023/02/hanging-out-sheila-liming-book-friendship-crisis.html">hanging out</a> , among other pleasures. What is there to be happy about again?<br><br> Be happy about this: For once, in terms of the economy, things are going well. They&#39;re great. They&#39;re as good as they ever have been. I promise.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 11:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/us-economy-labor-market-inflation-housing/674790/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/us-economy-labor-market-inflation-housing/674790/</item></channel></rss>